{"title_page": "Central West (New South Wales)", "text_new": "{{morefootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = region    <!-- This box may still be removed if it is objected to -->\n| name     = Central West\n| state    = nsw\n| image    = LachlanAtCowra.JPG\n| caption  = <small>The Lachlan River at [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]]</small>\n| coordinates = \n| lga      = [[Bathurst Region]], [[City of Orange (New South Wales)|City of Orange]], [[Cowra Shire]], [[Parkes Shire]], [[City of Lithgow]], [[Oberon Shire]], [[Mid-Western Regional Council]], [[Forbes Shire]], [[Cabonne Shire]], [[Weddin Shire]], [[Bland Shire]], [[Lachlan Shire]]\n| pop      = 209,810\n| pop_year = 30 June 2016\n| pop_footnotes = <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015843/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Bathurst|Bathurst]]\n| stategov2 = [[Electoral district of Cootamundra|Cootamundra]]\n| stategov3 = [[Electoral district of Dubbo|Dubbo]]\n| stategov4 = [[Electoral district of Orange|Orange]] \n| fedgov   = [[Division of Calare|Calare]]\n| near-nw      = [[Orana (New South Wales)|Orana]]\n| near-n       = [[Hunter Region|Upper Hunter]]\n| near-ne      = [[Hunter Region|Hunter]]\n| near-w       = [[Orana (New South Wales)|Orana]]\n| near-e       = [[Greater Blue Mountains Area]]\n| near-sw      = [[South West Slopes]]\n| near-s       = [[South West Slopes]]\n| near-se      = [[Southern Tablelands]]\n}}\n\n'''The Central West''' is a region of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. The region is geographically in eastern New South Wales, in the area west of the [[Blue Mountains (Australia)|Blue Mountains]], which are west of [[Sydney]]. It has an area of {{convert|63262|km2}}.<ref name=\"BusinessNSW\">[http://www.business.nsw.gov.au/region/profiles/Central%20West.htm Central West Region - the agricultural heart of New South Wales] website of New South Wales Department of State and Regional Development, accessed 12 November 2006</ref> The region includes the area meteorologically defined as the [[Central Tablelands]], located in the eastern part of the region.\n\nMajor population and service centres in the Central West include the cities of [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]] and [[Orange, New South Wales|Orange]]; and the large towns of [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]], [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]], [[Mudgee]] and [[Parkes, New South Wales|Parkes]]. Bathurst and Orange are home to campuses of [[Charles Sturt University]], and Lithgow housing the [[University of Notre Dame Australia|University of Notre Dame Regional Clinical School]].\n\n== Cities and towns ==\nThe Central West includes two cities: [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]] and [[Orange, New South Wales|Orange]]; four large towns: [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]], [[Mudgee]], [[Parkes, New South Wales|Parkes]] and [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]]; smaller centres, such as [[Oberon, New South Wales|Oberon]] and [[Forbes, New South Wales|Forbes]]; and small towns and villages such as [[Canowindra, New South Wales|Canowindra]], [[Cudal, New South Wales|Cudal]], [[Molong, New South Wales|Molong]], [[Grenfell, New South Wales|Grenfell]], [[West Wyalong, New South Wales|West Wyalong]], [[Portland, New South Wales|Portland]], [[Wallerawang]], [[Condobolin, New South Wales|Condobolin]] and [[Eugowra, New South Wales|Eugowra]].\n\n===Demography and area===\nThe following [[Local government areas of New South Wales|local government areas]] are contained within the region:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+Population by Local Government Area\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Central West rank\n! scope=\"col\" | Local Government Area\n! scope=\"col\" | Population 30 June  2016<ref name=\"3218.0\">{{cite web |publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics |title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2016 |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015843/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" | 10 year growth rate\n! scope=\"col\" | Population density (people/km<sup>2</sup>)\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 1\n| [[Bathurst Regional Council]]\n| 42,389\n| 14.8\n| 11.1\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 2\n| [[City of Orange (New South Wales)|Orange City]]\n| 41,384\n| 13.8\n| 145.6\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 3\n| [[Mid-Western Regional Council]]\n| 24,569\n| 13.5\n| 2.8\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 4\n| [[City of Lithgow|City of Lithgow Council]]\n| 21,524\n| 6.6\n| 4.8\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 7\n| [[Parkes Shire|Parkes Shire Council]]\n| 14,946\n| 2.4\n| 2.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 8\n| [[Cabonne Shire Council|Cabonne Shire]]\n| 13,625\n| 7.8\n| 2.3\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 9\n| [[Cowra Shire Council|Cowra Shire]]\n| 12,673\n| -0.6\n| 4.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 10\n| [[Forbes Shire Council|Forbes Shire]]\n| 9,808\n| 2.8\n| 2.1\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 11\n| [[Blayney Shire Council|Blayney Shire]]\n| 7,418\n| 10.0\n| 4.9\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 12\n| [[Lachlan Shire Council|Lachlan Shire]]\n| 6,352\n| -7.0\n| 0.4\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 13\n| [[Bland Shire Council|Bland Shire]]\n| 6,031\n| -2.9\n| 0.7\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 14\n| [[Oberon Council|Oberon Shire]]\n| 5,399\n| 4.2\n| 1.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 15\n| [[Weddin Shire Council|Weddin Shire]]\n| 3,692\n| -0.8\n| 1.1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Central West\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 209,810\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 8.5\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 3.0\n|}\n\n== Terrain ==\nThe Central West's east is higher, wetter and hillier and supports orchards, [[vineyard]]s, vegetable-growing and pastoralism. The west is flatter and drier and supports grain crops and pastoralism.\n\n== Major highways ==\nThe Central West region is traversed by the [[Great Western Highway]], the [[Mid-Western Highway]], the [[Mitchell Highway]], the [[Newell Highway]] and the [[Castlereagh Highway]].\n\n== Media ==\nThe Central West has several radio stations, including 97.9 2LVR (a community radio station), 105.1 [[2GZ|2GZFM]], 105.9 [[Star FM]], 107.9 [[Move FM]], 107.5 Community Radio, 103.5 [[Rhema FM]] and [[2EL|1089AM]] \u2014 a commercial station that gets most of its programming from [[2SM]] in Sydney. Other electronic media are represented by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] with both television and radio broadcasting; and by television stations [[Prime7]], [[WIN Television|WIN]], and [[Southern Cross Nine]].\n\nTwo major newspapers are published in the region, the ''[[Central Western Daily]]'' newspaper is published in Orange and the [[The Western Advocate (Bathurst, New South Wales)|Western Advocate]] in Bathurst. Numerous other local papers serve the remaining large towns.\n\n== History ==\nThe Central West area was originally inhabited by the Wiradjuri people. The first white explorer, George Wilson Evans, entered the [[Wyangala#Water resources|Lachlan Valley]] in 1815. He named the area the Oxley Plains after his superior the surveyor-general, John Oxley. In 1817 he deemed the area unfit for white settlement. A Military Depot was established not long after at Soldiers Flat near present-day Billimari. Arthur Ranken and James Sloan, from Bathurst, were amongst the first white settlers on the Lachlan. They moved to the area in 1831.\n\nIn the 1850s many gold prospectors passed through headed for gold fields at Lambing Flat ([[Young, New South Wales|Young]]) and [[Grenfell, New South Wales|Grenfell]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Central West (New South Wales)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091112022439/http://www.bom.gov.au/weather/nsw/nsw-forecast-map.shtml NSW Forecast Areas map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080905131130/http://www.dlg.nsw.gov.au/dlg/dlghome/dlg_regions.asp?mi=0&ml=8&regiontype=1&region=CW Department of Local Government page for the region] listing links to council pages\n* [http://www.dmoz.org/Regional/Oceania/Australia/New_South_Wales/Regions/Central_West/ \"Open Directory\" listing]\n\n{{Regions of New South Wales |state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Regions of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Central West (New South Wales)| ]]\n[[Category:Newell Highway]]\n", "text_old": "{{morefootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = region    <!-- This box may still be removed if it is objected to -->\n| name     = Central West\n| state    = nsw\n| image    = LachlanAtCowra.JPG\n| caption  = <small>The Lachlan River at [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]]</small>\n| coordinates = \n| lga      = [[Bathurst Region]], [[City of Orange (New South Wales)|City of Orange]], [[Cowra Shire]], [[Parkes Shire]], [[City of Lithgow]], [[Oberon Shire]], [[Mid-Western Regional Council]], [[Forbes Shire]], [[Cabonne Shire]], [[Weddin Shire]], [[Bland Shire]], [[Lachlan Shire]]\n| pop      = 209,810\n| pop_year = 30 June 2016\n| pop_footnotes = <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015843/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |archive-date=5 