]'' newspaper is published in Orange and the [[The Western Advocate (Bathurst, New South Wales)|Western Advocate]] in Bathurst. Numerous other local papers serve the remaining large towns.\n\n== History ==\nThe Central West area was originally inhabited by the Wiradjuri people. The first white explorer, George Wilson Evans, entered the [[Wyangala#Water resources|Lachlan Valley]] in 1815. He named the area the Oxley Plains after his superior the surveyor-general, John Oxley. In 1817 he deemed the area unfit for white settlement. A Military Depot was established not long after at Soldiers Flat near present-day Billimari. Arthur Ranken and James Sloan, from Bathurst, were amongst the first white settlers on the Lachlan. They moved to the area in 1831.\n\nIn the 1850s many gold prospectors passed through headed for gold fields at Lambing Flat ([[Young, New South Wales|Young]]) and [[Grenfell, New South Wales|Grenfell]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Central West (New South Wales)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091112022439/http://www.bom.gov.au/weather/nsw/nsw-forecast-map.shtml NSW Forecast Areas map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080905131130/http://www.dlg.nsw.gov.au/dlg/dlghome/dlg_regions.asp?mi=0&ml=8&regiontype=1&region=CW Department of Local Government page for the region] listing links to council pages\n* [http://www.dmoz.org/Regional/Oceania/Australia/New_South_Wales/Regions/Central_West/ \"Open Directory\" listing]\n\n{{Regions of New South Wales |state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Regions of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Central West (New South Wales)| ]]\n[[Category:Newell Highway]]\n", "name_user": "Snowbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_West_(New_South_Wales)"}
{"title_page": "Ryan-Mark Parsons", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ryan-Mark Parsons\n| honorific_suffix   = [[FRSA]]\n| image              = Ryan-Mark Parsons at Television Centre, London.jpg\n| caption            = Parsons at Television Centre, London in 2020\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|2000|04|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[London, United Kingdom]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = Babington House School\n| occupation         = Media Personality \u2219 Entrepreneur\n| known_for          = Youngest-ever Candidate on The Apprentice\n| television         = ''[[The Apprentice (British TV series)|The Apprentice]]''<br>''[[The Apprentice: You're Fired]]''<br>''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''<br>''[[London Live]]''<br>''[[BBC London News]]''\n| honours            = Fellowship of Royal Society of Arts\n| website            = {{url|https://ryanmarkparsons.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Ryan-Mark Parsons''', [[FRSA]] is a media personality and entrepreneur. He is best known for being the youngest-ever candidate on the [[BBC One]] show [[The Apprentice (British TV series)|The Apprentice]] and featured in a controversial debate on [[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/4tS1HPmrqcR3dz8Vpb4HfvQ/ryan-mark-parsons|title=BBC One - The Apprentice, Series 15 - Ryan-Mark Parsons|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2019/10/09/apprentice-2019-contestants-who-candidates-new-series-lord-sugar/ryan-mark-parsons/|title=The Apprentice 2019 contestants: meet Lord Sugar's remaining candidates|date=2019-10-09|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-11-23|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/23/apprentices-ryan-mark-parsons-infuriates-gmb-viewers-promotes-sale-koala-fur-charity-12107871/|title=The Apprentice's Ryan-Mark Parsons claims koala fur should be sold for charity|date=2020-01-23|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> Parsons has made several appearances as a guest on various TV and radio shows; as well as speeches at [[Piccadilly Theatre]], [[Palace of Westminster|Speaker's House]] and [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] to [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and other dignitaries.\n\nParsons was born in London, United Kingdom. He was educated at Babington House School and chose not to go to university. In 2015, he came first in a Bromley regional public speaking competition and was later selected to compete at the national final for the [[Jack Petchey]] 'Speak Out' at Piccadilly Theatre, taking third place overall.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/beckenham-pupil-through-to-final-of-public-speaking-competition-1-4018316|title=Beckenham pupil through to final of public speaking competition|last1=Linney|first1=Sarah|work=Bromley Times|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000b96t|title=BBC One - The Apprentice, Series 15, Finland Advertising|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harrisbeckenham.org.uk/28/latest-news/post/27/triumph-as-ryan-secures-3rd-place-in-the-grand-final-of-the-jack-petchey-speak-out-challenge|title=TRIUMPH AS RYAN SECURES 3RD PLACE IN THE GRAND FINAL OF THE JACK PETCHEY SPEAK OUT CHALLENGE - Latest News - Harris Academy Beckenham|website=www.harrisbeckenham.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetab.com/uk/2019/10/09/the-apprentice-universities-2019-128121|title=This is where all The Apprentice 2019 candidates went to uni|date=2019-10-09|website=UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n\n== The Apprentice 2019 ==\nParsons joined The Apprentice aged 19, known to be the youngest-ever candidate since the show began in 2005. He described himself as having the ability to \"forge a connection with anyone\".<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2019-11-20/apprentice-2019-ryan-mark-parsons/|title=Meet Apprentice 2019's Ryan-Mark Parsons, the show's youngest ever candidate|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://graziadaily.co.uk/life/tv-and-film/apprentice-2019/|title=The Apprentice Line Up Has Been Released So We've Made Some Predictions Based Mostly On Their Suits|date=2019-09-25|website=Grazia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> Parsons' performance was praised by Sean O'Grady, Associate Editor of [[The Independent]], who said the \u201ccherubic Ryan-Mark Parsons is the real winner of this series. He describes himself as \u201ca 60-year old in a teenager\u2019s body\u201d, and according to his BBC biography, his role model is [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]]. With his extravagant style, I can quite imagine him graciously opening a stately home\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-apprentice-final-review-carina-lepore-lottie-lion-ryan-mark-parsons-lord-sugar-scarlett-a9251706.html|title=This year's Apprentice winner is worthy and, most unusually, likeable \u2013 review|date=2019-12-18|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week Six, Parsons and a fellow candidate tested one of the rollercoasters at [[Thorpe Park]]; where Parsons was described to be \"screaming throughout the entire ride\". This sparked a significant online reaction, receiving 13,000 Twitter mentions and 10,000 hashtags used; making it one of the most talked about TV moments from 2019, revealed by [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a29721150/apprentice-rollercoaster-task-ryan-mark-lewis-saw/|title=The Apprentice contestants tested a rollercoaster and it was hilarious|last=Shenton|first=Zoe|date=2019-11-07|website=Cosmopolitan|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/film/2019121982252/most-talked-about-moments-tv-2019/|title=The most talked about TV moments of 2019 have been revealed \u2013 and they might surprise you|date=2019-12-19|website=HELLO!|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nOn Week Seven, Parsons and another candidate were told to get off a [[Finnair]] plane bound for Finland due to the airline failing to cater for nut allergies. In a statement, Parsons told The Independent \"I'm astounded by the airline's policy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/apprentice-nut-allergy-finnair-bbc-ryan-mark-parsons-pamela-laird-a9201016.html|title=Apprentice contestants with life-threatening nut allergies told by airline: \u2018If you have an issue, get off the plane\u2019|date=2019-11-13|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n=== Aftermath ===\nParsons was fired in Week Eight of the competition, and his exit interviews caused controversy after calling fellow candidates a \"waste of space\" and \"desperate\".<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/the-apprentice-2019-episode-8-ryan-mark-parsons-fired-lord-alan-sugar-lottie-lion-thomas-a9210546.html|title=The Apprentice candidate Ryan-Mark Parsons speaks out after being fired|date=2019-11-20|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2019-11-20/the-apprentice-ryan-mark-fired/|title=The Apprentice\u2019s Ryan-Mark Parsons claims other fired candidates are \"desperate\"|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/the-apprentice-2019-who-left-fired-last-week-episode-8-ryan-mark-parsons-recap-642381|title=Here's who was fired from The Apprentice 2019|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetab.com/uk/2019/11/21/the-apprentice-ryan-mark-133087|title=A tribute to Ryan-Mark: The Apprentice King who was gone too soon|date=2019-11-21|website=UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> Following his firing, a conversation was leaked about him insulting another contestant, leading to accusations of bullying. Parsons \"branded his co-star 'ugly' and says she looks like a man in drag\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/12/02/apprentices-marianne-rawlins-close-tears-compared-man-drag-rival-ryan-mark-parsons-11257128/|title=The Apprentice\u2019s Marianne Rawlins \u2018close to tears\u2019 after being compared to \u2018man in drag\u2019 by rival Ryan-Mark Parsons|last=|first=|date=2019-12-02|website=Metro|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Weeks following the series, Parsons had an altercation with a different contestant, after they criticised Parsons for \"charging fans for photos\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/ryanmark-parsons-lottie-lion-photographs-feud-the-apprentice-a4323471.html|title=Ryan-Mark slams Apprentice co-star Lottie in signed pictures dispute|date=2019-12-31|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> It was also reported that Parsons was hospitalised after he dropped \"\u00a31000 caviar on his foot\" and the star was \"rushed to hospital\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ok.co.uk/celebrity-news/apprentice-caviar-accident-foot-hospital-20999461|title=The Apprentice star Ryan-Mark Parsons is hospitalised after dropping \u00a31000 of caviar on his foot|last=|first=|date=2019-11-30|website=OK! Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was around the same time, Parsons was caught by press eating [[McDonald's]] at one of their London restaurants with a knife and fork. More recently in January 2020, Parsons was slammed for lashing out at a \"family friend after they gifted him a pair of pyjamas from budget high street store Primark\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/posh-apprentice-star-ryan-mark-21219873|title=Apprentice star Ryan-Mark lashes out at pal because they gifted him Primark pj's|last=Kent|first=Sara-Aisha|date=2020-01-05|website=Daily Mirror|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Good Morning Britain 2020 ==\nOn 23 January 2020, Parsons featured as a celebrity panelist on Good Morning Britain to debate whether \"Australia should 'sell koala fur' to fund bushfire aid\". Parsons made the argument that the dead koala fur could be sold \"to raise money for the injured animals in the rescue centres\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/23/apprentices-ryan-mark-parsons-infuriates-gmb-viewers-promotes-sale-koala-fur-charity-12107871/|title=The Apprentice's Ryan-Mark Parsons claims koala fur should be sold for charity|date=2020-01-23|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> This was criticised by animal rights activist, [[Wendy Turner Webster]], who called his idea \"grotesque\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/grotesque-british-entrepreneur-shot-down-over-plan-to-sell-dead-koala-fur-as-bushfire-fundraiser-20200124-p53ubu.html|title='Grotesque': British entrepreneur shot down over plan to sell koala fur as bushfire fundraiser|last=Shields|first=Bevan|date=2020-01-24|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> alongside presenter [[Susanna Reid]] labelling the suggestion as \"sick\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/apprentice-star-branded-sick-after-21341480|title=Apprentice star branded 'sick' after suggesting koala fur should be sold for charity|last=|first=|date=2020-01-23|website=Daily Mirror|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> He was met with strong public and media backlash from UK, Australian and New Zealand press, slamming Parsons for his \"vile\" and \"disgusting\" views.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12303231|title='Disgusting suggestion': Businessman's plan for dead koalas slammed|date=2020-01-24|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2020-01-26|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/news/bushfires/bushfire-crisis-apprentice-contestant-says-dead-koala-fur-should-be-sold-for-charity-c-661845|title=Businessman slammed over \u2018vile\u2019 plan for koalas killed in bushfire crisis|date=2020-01-23|website=7NEWS.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n== Radio appearances ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Talkradio]]: Julia Hartley-Brewer''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[BBC Radio 5 Live]]: Wake Up to Money''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[BBC Asian Network]]: Breakfast Show''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Hits Radio]]: Breakfast Show''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n'''[[National Television Awards]]'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! width=\"5%\" | Year\n! width=\"40%\" | Category\n! width=\"40%\" | Nominated work / Nominee\n! width=\"10%\" | Result\n! width=\"5%\" class=\"unsortable\" |{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2020\n|[[25th National Television Awards|Challenge Show]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''The Apprentice''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/nta-2020-winners-national-television-awards-live-itv-results-who-won-full-list-1378299|title=Ant and Dec win best presenter at NTAs for 19th year in a row|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n|}\n== Career ==\nBefore appearing on The Apprentice, Parsons worked as a [[Gucci]] Brand Ambassador in [[Harrods]] and in [[Aspinal of London]]; including several internships at the [[Palace of Westminster]], [[Matrix Chambers]], 5 King's Bench Walk, [[American International Group|AIG]] and [[National Health Service|NHS]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legalcheek.com/2019/09/the-apprentice-2019-former-matrix-mini-pupil-set-to-become-youngest-ever-contestant/|title=The Apprentice 2019: Former Matrix mini-pupil set to become youngest-ever contestant|date=2019-09-26|website=Legal Cheek|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n\nSince leaving the show, Parsons has expressed to continue work on television, saying \"I've been approached by different people for different opportunities\" and wouldn't rule out doing more media work.<ref name=\":12\" />\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://ryanmarkparsons.co.uk/ Official website]\n* [[imdbname:11152933|Ryan-Mark Parsons]] on [[IMDb]]\n* [https://instagram.com/ryanmarkparsons Instagram]\n* [https://twitter.com/ryanmarkparsons Twitter]\n* [https://youtube.com/ryanmarkparsons YouTube]\n* [https://www.linkedin.com/in/ryanmarkparsons LinkedIn]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from London]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n[[Category:Participants in British reality television series]]\n[[Category:The Apprentice (British TV series) candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ryan-Mark Parsons\n| honorific_suffix   = [[FRSA]]\n| image              = Ryan-Mark Parsons at Television Centre, London.jpg\n| caption            = Parsons at Television Centre, London in 2020\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|2000|04|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[London, United Kingdom]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = Babington House School\n| occupation         = Media Personality \u2219 Entrepreneur\n| known_for          = Youngest-ever Candidate on The Apprentice\n| television         = ''[[The Apprentice (British TV series)|The Apprentice]]''<br>''[[The Apprentice: You're Fired]]''<br>''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''<br>''[[London Live]]''<br>''[[BBC London News]]''\n| honours            = Fellowship of Royal Society of Arts\n| website            = {{url|https://ryanmarkparsons.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Ryan-Mark Parsons''', [[FRSA]] is a media personality and entrepreneur. He is best known for being the youngest-ever candidate on the [[BBC One]] show [[The Apprentice (British TV series)|The Apprentice]] and featured in a controversial debate on [[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/4tS1HPmrqcR3dz8Vpb4HfvQ/ryan-mark-parsons|title=BBC One - The Apprentice, Series 15 - Ryan-Mark Parsons|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2019/10/09/apprentice-2019-contestants-who-candidates-new-series-lord-sugar/ryan-mark-parsons/|title=The Apprentice 2019 contestants: meet Lord Sugar's remaining candidates|date=2019-10-09|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-11-23|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/23/apprentices-ryan-mark-parsons-infuriates-gmb-viewers-promotes-sale-koala-fur-charity-12107871/|title=The Apprentice's Ryan-Mark Parsons claims koala fur should be sold for charity|date=2020-01-23|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> Parsons has made several appearances as a guest on various TV and radio shows; as well as speeches at [[Piccadilly Theatre]], [[Palace of Westminster|Speaker's House]] and [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] to [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and other dignitaries.\n\nParsons was born in London, United Kingdom. He was educated at Babington House School and chose not to go to university. In 2015, he came first in a Bromley regional public speaking competition and was later selected to compete at the national final for the [[Jack Petchey]] 'Speak Out' at Piccadilly Theatre, taking third place overall.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/beckenham-pupil-through-to-final-of-public-speaking-competition-1-4018316|title=Beckenham pupil through to final of public speaking competition|last1=Linney|first1=Sarah|work=Bromley Times|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000b96t|title=BBC One - The Apprentice, Series 15, Finland Advertising|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harrisbeckenham.org.uk/28/latest-news/post/27/triumph-as-ryan-secures-3rd-place-in-the-grand-final-of-the-jack-petchey-speak-out-challenge|title=TRIUMPH AS RYAN SECURES 3RD PLACE IN THE GRAND FINAL OF THE JACK PETCHEY SPEAK OUT CHALLENGE - Latest News - Harris Academy Beckenham|website=www.harrisbeckenham.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetab.com/uk/2019/10/09/the-apprentice-universities-2019-128121|title=This is where all The Apprentice 2019 candidates went to uni|date=2019-10-09|website=UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n\n== The Apprentice 2019 ==\nParsons joined The Apprentice aged 19, known to be the youngest-ever candidate since the show began in 2005. He described himself as having the ability to \"forge a connection with anyone\".<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2019-11-20/apprentice-2019-ryan-mark-parsons/|title=Meet Apprentice 2019's Ryan-Mark Parsons, the show's youngest ever candidate|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://graziadaily.co.uk/life/tv-and-film/apprentice-2019/|title=The Apprentice Line Up Has Been Released So We've Made Some Predictions Based Mostly On Their Suits|date=2019-09-25|website=Grazia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> Parsons' performance was praised by Sean O'Grady, Associate Editor of [[The Independent]], who said the \u201ccherubic Ryan-Mark Parsons is the real winner of this series. He describes himself as \u201ca 60-year old in a teenager\u2019s body\u201d, and according to his BBC biography, his role model is [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]]. With his extravagant style, I can quite imagine him graciously opening a stately home\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-apprentice-final-review-carina-lepore-lottie-lion-ryan-mark-parsons-lord-sugar-scarlett-a9251706.html|title=This year's Apprentice winner is worthy and, most unusually, likeable \u2013 review|date=2019-12-18|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week Six, Parsons and a fellow candidate tested one of the rollercoasters at [[Thorpe Park]]; where Parsons was described to be \"screaming throughout the entire ride\". This sparked a significant online reaction, receiving 13,000 Twitter mentions and 10,000 hashtags used; making it one of the most talked about TV moments from 2019, revealed by [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a29721150/apprentice-rollercoaster-task-ryan-mark-lewis-saw/|title=The Apprentice contestants tested a rollercoaster and it was hilarious|last=Shenton|first=Zoe|date=2019-11-07|website=Cosmopolitan|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/film/2019121982252/most-talked-about-moments-tv-2019/|title=The most talked about TV moments of 2019 have been revealed \u2013 and they might surprise you|date=2019-12-19|website=HELLO!|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nOn Week Seven, Parsons and another candidate were told to get off a [[Finnair]] plane bound for Finland due to the airline failing to cater for nut allergies. In a statement, Parsons told The Independent \"I'm astounded by the airline's policy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/apprentice-nut-allergy-finnair-bbc-ryan-mark-parsons-pamela-laird-a9201016.html|title=Apprentice contestants with life-threatening nut allergies told by airline: \u2018If you have an issue, get off the plane\u2019|date=2019-11-13|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n=== Aftermath ===\nParsons was fired in Week Eight of the competition, and his exit interviews caused controversy after calling fellow candidates a \"waste of space\" and \"desperate\".<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/the-apprentice-2019-episode-8-ryan-mark-parsons-fired-lord-alan-sugar-lottie-lion-thomas-a9210546.html|title=The Apprentice candidate Ryan-Mark Parsons speaks out after being fired|date=2019-11-20|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2019-11-20/the-apprentice-ryan-mark-fired/|title=The Apprentice\u2019s Ryan-Mark Parsons claims other fired candidates are \"desperate\"|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/the-apprentice-2019-who-left-fired-last-week-episode-8-ryan-mark-parsons-recap-642381|title=Here's who was fired from The Apprentice 2019|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetab.com/uk/2019/11/21/the-apprentice-ryan-mark-133087|title=A tribute to Ryan-Mark: The Apprentice King who was gone too soon|date=2019-11-21|website=UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> Following his firing, a conversation was leaked about him insulting another contestant, leading to accusations of bullying. Parsons \"branded his co-star 'ugly' and says she looks like a man in drag\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/12/02/apprentices-marianne-rawlins-close-tears-compared-man-drag-rival-ryan-mark-parsons-11257128/|title=The Apprentice\u2019s Marianne Rawlins \u2018close to tears\u2019 after being compared to \u2018man in drag\u2019 by rival Ryan-Mark Parsons|last=|first=|date=2019-12-02|website=Metro|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Weeks following the series, Parsons had an altercation with a different contestant, after they criticised Parsons for \"charging fans for photos\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/ryanmark-parsons-lottie-lion-photographs-feud-the-apprentice-a4323471.html|title=Ryan-Mark slams Apprentice co-star Lottie in signed pictures dispute|date=2019-12-31|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> It was also reported that Parsons was hospitalised after he dropped \"\u00a31000 caviar on his foot\" and the star was \"rushed to hospital\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ok.co.uk/celebrity-news/apprentice-caviar-accident-foot-hospital-20999461|title=The Apprentice star Ryan-Mark Parsons is hospitalised after dropping \u00a31000 of caviar on his foot|last=|first=|date=2019-11-30|website=OK! Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was around the same time, Parsons was caught by press eating [[McDonald's]] at one of their London restaurants with a knife and fork. More recently in January 2020, Parsons was slammed for lashing out at a \"family friend after they gifted him a pair of pyjamas from budget high street store Primark\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/posh-apprentice-star-ryan-mark-21219873|title=Apprentice star Ryan-Mark lashes out at pal because they gifted him Primark pj's|last=Kent|first=Sara-Aisha|date=2020-01-05|website=Daily Mirror|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Good Morning Britain 2020 ==\nOn 23 January 2020, Parsons featured as a celebrity panelist on Good Morning Britain to debate whether \"Australia should 'sell koala fur' to fund bushfire aid\". Parsons made the argument that the dead koala fur could be sold \"to raise money for the injured animals in the rescue centres\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/23/apprentices-ryan-mark-parsons-infuriates-gmb-viewers-promotes-sale-koala-fur-charity-12107871/|title=The Apprentice's Ryan-Mark Parsons claims koala fur should be sold for charity|date=2020-01-23|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> This was criticised by animal rights activist, [[Wendy Turner Webster]], who called his idea \"grotesque\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/grotesque-british-entrepreneur-shot-down-over-plan-to-sell-dead-koala-fur-as-bushfire-fundraiser-20200124-p53ubu.html|title='Grotesque': British entrepreneur shot down over plan to sell koala fur as bushfire fundraiser|last=Shields|first=Bevan|date=2020-01-24|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> alongside presenter [[Susanna Reid]] labelling the suggestion as \"sick\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/apprentice-star-branded-sick-after-21341480|title=Apprentice star branded 'sick' after suggesting koala fur should be sold for charity|last=|first=|date=2020-01-23|website=Daily Mirror|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> He was met with strong public and media backlash from UK, Australian and New Zealand press, slamming Parsons for his \"vile\" and \"disgusting\" views.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12303231|title='Disgusting suggestion': Businessman's plan for dead koalas slammed|date=2020-01-24|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2020-01-26|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/news/bushfires/bushfire-crisis-apprentice-contestant-says-dead-koala-fur-should-be-sold-for-charity-c-661845|title=Businessman slammed over \u2018vile\u2019 plan for koalas killed in bushfire crisis|date=2020-01-23|website=7NEWS.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n== Radio appearances ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Talkradio]]: Julia Hartley-Brewer''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[BBC Radio 5 Live]]: Wake Up to Money''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[BBC Asian Network]]: Breakfast Show''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Hits Radio]]: Breakfast Show''\n|Himself\n|Guest\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n'''[[National Television Awards]]'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! width=\"5%\" | Year\n! width=\"40%\" | Category\n! width=\"40%\" | Nominated work / Nominee\n! width=\"10%\" | Result\n! width=\"5%\" class=\"unsortable\" |{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2020\n|[[25th National Television Awards|Challenge Show]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''The Apprentice Series 15''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/nta-2020-winners-national-television-awards-live-itv-results-who-won-full-list-1378299|title=Ant and Dec win best presenter at NTAs for 19th year in a row|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n|}\n== Career ==\nBefore appearing on The Apprentice, Parsons worked as a [[Gucci]] Brand Ambassador in [[Harrods]] and in [[Aspinal of London]]; including several internships at the [[Palace of Westminster]], [[Matrix Chambers]], 5 King's Bench Walk, [[American International Group|AIG]] and [[National Health Service|NHS]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legalcheek.com/2019/09/the-apprentice-2019-former-matrix-mini-pupil-set-to-become-youngest-ever-contestant/|title=The Apprentice 2019: Former Matrix mini-pupil set to become youngest-ever contestant|date=2019-09-26|website=Legal Cheek|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n\nSince leaving the show, Parsons has expressed to continue work on television, saying \"I've been approached by different people for different opportunities\" and wouldn't rule out doing more media work.<ref name=\":12\" />\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://ryanmarkparsons.co.uk/ Official website]\n* [[imdbname:11152933|Ryan-Mark Parsons]] on [[IMDb]]\n* [https://instagram.com/ryanmarkparsons Instagram]\n* [https://twitter.com/ryanmarkparsons Twitter]\n* [https://youtube.com/ryanmarkparsons YouTube]\n* [https://www.linkedin.com/in/ryanmarkparsons LinkedIn]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from London]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n[[Category:Participants in British reality television series]]\n[[Category:The Apprentice (British TV series) candidates]]\n", "name_user": "JPA24", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting change.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryan-Mark_Parsons"}
{"title_page": "Darwin, California", "text_new": "{{for|the former place with this name in Fresno County|Darwin, Fresno County, California}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Darwin\n|settlement_type          = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]]\n|image_skyline            = Darwin, California.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Darwin, California\n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = Inyo_County_California_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Darwin_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = Location in [[Inyo County, California|Inyo County]] and the state of [[California]]\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n| pushpin_map = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|California}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in California|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Inyo County, California|Inyo]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area------------------>\n|area_magnitude           = \n| unit_pref               = US\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>{{Cite US Gazetteer|2010|places|CA}}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi        = 1.345\n| area_land_sq_mi         = 1.345\n| area_water_sq_mi        = 0\n| area_total_km2          = 3.485\n| area_land_km2           = 3.485\n| area_water_km2          = 0\n| area_water_percent      = 0\n| area_note               =\n\n|elevation_ft             = 4790\n|elevation_m              = 1460\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=gnis>{{gnis|241269}}</ref>\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 36\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific (PST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -8\n|coordinates              = {{coord|36|16|05|N|117|35|30|W|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|timezone_DST             = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -7\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 93522\n|area_code_type           = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area codes]]\n|area_code                = [[Area codes 442 and 760|442/760]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 06-18030\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0241269\n|footnotes                = \n|website                  = \n}}\n[[Image:Darwincalifornia.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Downtown Darwin in 2003]]\n\n'''Darwin''' is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated mining community]] in [[Inyo County, California]], United States. It is located {{convert|22|mi|km|0}} southeast of [[Keeler, California|Keeler]],<ref name=CGN>{{California's Geographic Names|1158}}</ref> at an elevation of {{convert|4790|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=gnis /> The population was 43 at the 2010 census, down from 54 at the 2000 census.\n\n==History==\nIt is named after Dr. [[Darwin French]]. According to Erwin Gudde, Dr French of Fort Tejon was with a party of prospectors in the area during the fall of 1850.  Dr French also led a party into [[Death Valley]] in 1860 to search for the mythical Gunsight Lode via the local wash, lending his first name to the wash, canyon and future town.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gudde|first1=Erwin G.|title=California place names : the origin and etymology of current geographical names|date=1998|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0520213165|page=[https://archive.org/details/californiaplacen00gudd/page/102 102]|edition=4th ed., rev. and enl.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/californiaplacen00gudd/page/102}}</ref>\n\nSilver and lead discovery at the place led to the founding of a settlement in 1874.<ref name=CGN /><ref>{{cite book |first=Robert P. |last=Palazzo |title=Darwin, California |year=1996}}</ref> A post office opened in 1875, closed for a time in 1902, and remains open.<ref>{{cite book |first=Robert P. |last=Palazzo |title=Inyo County Post Offices and Postmasters 1866-1966 |year=2005}}</ref> The town prospered when Eichbaum Toll Road opened in 1926, opening Death Valley from the west.  When Death Valley became a National Monument in 1933 it was decided to buy the toll road to allow free access to the new park.  In 1937, a new cutoff bypassed Darwin, isolating the town.<ref>{{cite news |first=Fitzhugh L. |last=Minnigerodee |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/10/24/archives/road-joins-extremes-highway-to-death-valley-links-high-and-low.html |title=Road Joins 'Extremes' |date=October 24, 1937 |p=8}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the town was the subject of a documentary film, titled [[Darwin (2011 film)|''Darwin'']]. In April 2012, [[BBC News]] featured a video of local residents describing their wishes to replace [[dial-up Internet access]] with [[broadband]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Darwin, the town trapped by dial-up internet\n| work = BBC News\n| access-date = 2012-04-03\n| date = 2012-04-02\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-17569954\n}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|1.3|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land. The census definition of the area was created by the Census Bureau for statistical purposes and may not precisely correspond to local understanding of the area with the same name.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|access-date=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\nFor statistical purposes, the [[United States Census Bureau]] has defined Darwin as a [[census-designated place]] (CDP).\n\n===2010===\nThe [[2010 United States Census]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0618030|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140715024352/http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0618030|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 15, 2014|title=2010 Census Interactive Population Search: CA - Darwin CDP|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|access-date=July 12, 2014}}</ref> reported that Darwin had a population of 43. The [[population density]] was 32.0 people per square mile (12.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of Darwin was 38 (88%) [[White (U.S. Census)|white]], 0 (0%) [[African American (U.S. Census)|black]], 2 (5%) [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1 (2%) [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian American]], 1 (2%) [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0 (0%) from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1 (2%) from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2 people (5%).\n\nThe Census reported that 43 people (100% of the population) lived in households; none lived in non-institutionalized group quarters or were institutionalized.\n\nThere were 28 households, out of which 0 (0%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 11 (39%) were [[marriage|opposite-sex married couples]] living together, 0 (0%) had a female householder with no husband present, and 1 (4%) had a male householder with no wife present. There were 1 (4%) [[POSSLQ|unmarried opposite-sex partnerships]] and 0 (0%) [[same-sex partnerships|same-sex married couples or partnerships]]. 14 households (50%) were made up of individuals, and 9 (32%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.5. There were 12 [[family (U.S. Census)|families]] (43% of all households); the average family size was 2.1.\n\nThe population was spread out with 0 people (0%) under the age of 18, 0 people (0%) aged 18 to 24, 2 people (5%) aged 25 to 44, 20 people (47%) aged 45 to 64, and 21 people (49%) who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 63.5 years. For every 100 females, there were 168.8 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 168.8 males.\n\nThere were 46 housing units at an average density of 34.2 per square mile (13.2/km\u00b2), of which 28 were occupied, of which 24 (86%) were owner-occupied and 4 (14%) were occupied by renters. The homeowner vacancy rate was 4%; the rental vacancy rate was 0%. 37 people (86% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units, and 6 people (14%) lived in rental housing units.\n\n===2000===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |access-date=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 54 people, 36 households, and 14 families residing in the CDP. The [[population density]] was 39.3 people per square mile (15.1/km\u00b2). There were 54 housing units at an average density of 39.3 per square mile (15.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the CDP was 91% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 2% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 4% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], and 4% from two or more races. 6% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 36 households out of which 8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 22% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 14% had a female householder with no husband present, and 6% were non-families. 56% of all households were made up of individuals and 8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.5 and the average family size was 2.0.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 6% under the age of 18, 2% from 18 to 24, 17% from 25 to 44, 59% from 45 to 64, and 17% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 53 years. For every 100 females, there were 145.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 142.9 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $13,333, and the median income for a family was $15,000. Males had a median income of under $2500 versus $36,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $11,048. There were 33% of families and 38% of the population living below the [[poverty line]], including 100% of under eighteens and none of those over 64.\n\n==Government==\nIn the [[California State Legislature|state legislature]], Darwin is in {{Representative|casd|8|fmt=sdistrict}},<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://senate.ca.gov/senators |title=Senators |access-date=April 11, 2013 |publisher=State of California}}</ref> and {{Representative|caad|26|fmt=adistrict}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://assembly.ca.gov/assemblymembers |title=Members Assembly |accessdate=April 11, 2013 |publisher=State of California}}</ref>\n\nFederally, Darwin is in {{Representative|cacd|8|fmt=district}}.<ref>{{Cite GovTrack|CA|8|access-date=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Darwin Monument at the Intersection of HWY 190 and Darwin Road.jpg|thumb|This monument heralds the entrance to the hamlet of Darwin, some seven of so miles southeast down Darwin Road. 2020.\nFile:Darwin Historic Marker at the Intersection of HWY 190 and Darwin Road.jpg|thumb|Interesting historic providing some early history of Darwin's founding. 2020.\nFile:Approaching Darwin on Darwin Road.jpg|thumb|Little to no traffic in this peaceful, almost somnolent town. 2020.\nFile:A view from Outside of Darwin along Darwin Road.jpg|thumb|This former mining community is nicely nestled among the mountains that once made it temporarily rich. 2020.\nFile:Another look at Darwin While Driving into Town.jpg|thumb|The town is nearly as stark and calm as the nearby hills and mountains. 2020.\nFile:Proceeding into Darwin.jpg|thumb|Pavement ends in a few hundred yards. Much of the town after that is laid out on dirt roads. 2020.\nFile:A look at Darwin to the North While Driving into Town.jpg|thumb|Darwin is another Mojave Desert living ghost town, set high in the mountains of Inyo County, California.2020.\nFile:More do it yourself housing in Darwin, California.jpg|thumb|Modest and casual, the atmosphere of Darwin benefits the independent townsfolk who live there. 2020.\nFile:BLM Road Sign from Darwin Road.jpg|thumb|This sign marks one of the many dirt and often four-wheel-drive roads to the backcountry. 2020.\nFile:Heading into the Mountains of Darwin for a Nighttime Fluorescent Mineral Hunt.jpg|thumb|A network of BLM roads provides access to old mines and their dumps full of assorted minerals that react to ultraviolet lamps.2020.\nFile:A View while Navigating the Many Twists and Turns of the BLM dirt Roads north of Darwin.jpg|thumb|Good maps and sat based electronics are essential for navigating in and out of this territory. 2020.\nFile:Group of Rocks under Shortwave UV from a Mine Dump Near Darwin.jpg|thumb|This group of rocks fairly represents what we found with several hours of looking at night.\n</gallery>\n==See also==\n*[[Darwin Falls]]\n*[[Darwin Falls Wilderness]]\n*[[Darwin Hills]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Palazzo, Robert P. ''Darwin, California'', Lake Grove, OR: Western Places, 1996. The history of the boom and bust of this mining town from 1874-1878.\n* Palazzo, Robert P.  \"Post Offices and Postmasters of Inyo County, California 1866-1966\", Fernley, NV: MacDonald, 2005.\n\n{{Inyo County, California}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1875 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in California]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Inyo County, California]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1875]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Mojave Desert]]\n[[Category:Mining communities in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the former place with this name in Fresno County|Darwin, Fresno County, California}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Darwin\n|settlement_type          = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]]\n|image_skyline            = Darwin, California.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Darwin, California\n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = Inyo_County_California_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Darwin_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = Location in [[Inyo County, California|Inyo County]] and the state of [[California]]\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n| pushpin_map = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|California}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in California|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Inyo County, California|Inyo]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area------------------>\n|area_magnitude           = \n| unit_pref               = US\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>{{Cite US Gazetteer|2010|places|CA}}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi        = 1.345\n| area_land_sq_mi         = 1.345\n| area_water_sq_mi        = 0\n| area_total_km2          = 3.485\n| area_land_km2           = 3.485\n| area_water_km2          = 0\n| area_water_percent      = 0\n| area_note               =\n\n|elevation_ft             = 4790\n|elevation_m              = 1460\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=gnis>{{gnis|241269}}</ref>\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 36\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific (PST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -8\n|coordinates              = {{coord|36|16|05|N|117|35|30|W|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|timezone_DST             = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -7\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 93522\n|area_code_type           = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area codes]]\n|area_code                = [[Area codes 442 and 760|442/760]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 06-18030\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0241269\n|footnotes                = \n|website                  = \n}}\n[[Image:Darwincalifornia.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Downtown Darwin in 2003]]\n\n'''Darwin''' is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated mining community]] in [[Inyo County, California]], United States. It is located {{convert|22|mi|km|0}} southeast of [[Keeler, California|Keeler]],<ref name=CGN>{{California's Geographic Names|1158}}</ref> at an elevation of {{convert|4790|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=gnis /> The population was 43 at the 2010 census, down from 54 at the 2000 census.\n\n==History==\nIt is named after Dr. [[Darwin French]]. According to Erwin Gudde, Dr French of Fort Tejon was with a party of prospectors in the area during the fall of 1850.  Dr French also led a party into [[Death Valley]] in 1860 to search for the mythical Gunsight Lode via the local wash, lending his first name to the wash, canyon and future town.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gudde|first1=Erwin G.|title=California place names : the origin and etymology of current geographical names|date=1998|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0520213165|page=[https://archive.org/details/californiaplacen00gudd/page/102 102]|edition=4th ed., rev. and enl.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/californiaplacen00gudd/page/102}}</ref>\n\nSilver and lead discovery at the place led to the founding of a settlement in 1874.<ref name=CGN /><ref>{{cite book |first=Robert P. |last=Palazzo |title=Darwin, California |year=1996}}</ref> A post office opened in 1875, closed for a time in 1902, and remains open.<ref>{{cite book |first=Robert P. |last=Palazzo |title=Inyo County Post Offices and Postmasters 1866-1966 |year=2005}}</ref> The town prospered when Eichbaum Toll Road opened in 1926, opening Death Valley from the west.  When Death Valley became a National Monument in 1933 it was decided to buy the toll road to allow free access to the new park.  In 1937, a new cutoff bypassed Darwin, isolating the town.<ref>{{cite news |first=Fitzhugh L. |last=Minnigerodee |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/10/24/archives/road-joins-extremes-highway-to-death-valley-links-high-and-low.html |title=Road Joins 'Extremes' |date=October 24, 1937 |p=8}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the town was the subject of a documentary film, titled [[Darwin (2011 film)|''Darwin'']]. In April 2012, [[BBC News]] featured a video of local residents describing their wishes to replace [[dial-up Internet access]] with [[broadband]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Darwin, the town trapped by dial-up internet\n| work = BBC News\n| access-date = 2012-04-03\n| date = 2012-04-02\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-17569954\n}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|1.3|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land. The census definition of the area was created by the Census Bureau for statistical purposes and may not precisely correspond to local understanding of the area with the same name.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|access-date=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\nFor statistical purposes, the [[United States Census Bureau]] has defined Darwin as a [[census-designated place]] (CDP).\n\n===2010===\nThe [[2010 United States Census]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0618030|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140715024352/http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0618030|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 15, 2014|title=2010 Census Interactive Population Search: CA - Darwin CDP|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|access-date=July 12, 2014}}</ref> reported that Darwin had a population of 43. The [[population density]] was 32.0 people per square mile (12.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of Darwin was 38 (88%) [[White (U.S. Census)|white]], 0 (0%) [[African American (U.S. Census)|black]], 2 (5%) [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1 (2%) [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian American]], 1 (2%) [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0 (0%) from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1 (2%) from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2 people (5%).\n\nThe Census reported that 43 people (100% of the population) lived in households; none lived in non-institutionalized group quarters or were institutionalized.\n\nThere were 28 households, out of which 0 (0%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 11 (39%) were [[marriage|opposite-sex married couples]] living together, 0 (0%) had a female householder with no husband present, and 1 (4%) had a male householder with no wife present. There were 1 (4%) [[POSSLQ|unmarried opposite-sex partnerships]] and 0 (0%) [[same-sex partnerships|same-sex married couples or partnerships]]. 14 households (50%) were made up of individuals, and 9 (32%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.5. There were 12 [[family (U.S. Census)|families]] (43% of all households); the average family size was 2.1.\n\nThe population was spread out with 0 people (0%) under the age of 18, 0 people (0%) aged 18 to 24, 2 people (5%) aged 25 to 44, 20 people (47%) aged 45 to 64, and 21 people (49%) who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 63.5 years. For every 100 females, there were 168.8 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 168.8 males.\n\nThere were 46 housing units at an average density of 34.2 per square mile (13.2/km\u00b2), of which 28 were occupied, of which 24 (86%) were owner-occupied and 4 (14%) were occupied by renters. The homeowner vacancy rate was 4%; the rental vacancy rate was 0%. 37 people (86% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units, and 6 people (14%) lived in rental housing units.\n\n===2000===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |access-date=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 54 people, 36 households, and 14 families residing in the CDP. The [[population density]] was 39.3 people per square mile (15.1/km\u00b2). There were 54 housing units at an average density of 39.3 per square mile (15.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the CDP was 91% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 2% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 4% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], and 4% from two or more races. 6% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 36 households out of which 8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 22% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 14% had a female householder with no husband present, and 6% were non-families. 56% of all households were made up of individuals and 8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.5 and the average family size was 2.0.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 6% under the age of 18, 2% from 18 to 24, 17% from 25 to 44, 59% from 45 to 64, and 17% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 53 years. For every 100 females, there were 145.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 142.9 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $13,333, and the median income for a family was $15,000. Males had a median income of under $2500 versus $36,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $11,048. There were 33% of families and 38% of the population living below the [[poverty line]], including 100% of under eighteens and none of those over 64.\n\n==Government==\nIn the [[California State Legislature|state legislature]], Darwin is in {{Representative|casd|8|fmt=sdistrict}},<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://senate.ca.gov/senators |title=Senators |access-date=April 11, 2013 |publisher=State of California}}</ref> and {{Representative|caad|26|fmt=adistrict}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://assembly.ca.gov/assemblymembers |title=Members Assembly |accessdate=April 11, 2013 |publisher=State of California}}</ref>\n\nFederally, Darwin is in {{Representative|cacd|8|fmt=district}}.<ref>{{Cite GovTrack|CA|8|access-date=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Darwin Falls]]\n*[[Darwin Falls Wilderness]]\n*[[Darwin Hills]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Palazzo, Robert P. ''Darwin, California'', Lake Grove, OR: Western Places, 1996. The history of the boom and bust of this mining town from 1874-1878.\n* Palazzo, Robert P.  \"Post Offices and Postmasters of Inyo County, California 1866-1966\", Fernley, NV: MacDonald, 2005.\n\n{{Inyo County, California}}