History of the Achaemenid Empire, 550\u2013330 BCE\n| year                          = 2014\n| publisher                     = Cambridge University Press\n| url                           = https://books.google.com/?id=__xGAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| ref                           = harv\n| isbn                         = 9781107652729\n}}\n\n\n{{Book of Daniel}}\n\n\n[[Category:Darius the Mede| ]]\n[[Category:Babylonian kings]]\n[[Category:Book of Daniel]]\n[[Category:Cyrus the Great]]\n[[Category:Hebrew Bible words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Jewish mythology]]\n[[Category:Jewish Babylonian history]]\n[[Category:Legendary rulers]]\n[[Category:Median people]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of the Hebrew Bible]]\n[[Category:Mythological kings]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n", "name_user": "Tgeorgescu", "label": "safe", "comment": "it is not doubtful", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darius_the_Mede"}
{"title_page": "Saara Kuugongelwa", "text_new": "{{short description|Prime Minister of Namibia}}\n{{Expert needed|1=Namibia|ex2=Africa|ex3=Politics|ex4=Economics|reason=An incumbent prime minister, especially if she is the woman to hold the position, should not have this short of an article|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix  = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila\n|honorific-suffix  = MP\n|image        = 2020 Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila.jpg\n|office       = 4th [[Prime Minister of Namibia]]\n|president    = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start   = 21 March 2015\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = Hage Geingob\n|successor    =\n\n|office1      = Minister of Finance\n|president1   = [[Sam Nujoma]]<br/>[[Hifikepunye Pohamba]]<br/>Hage Geingob\n|term_start1  = 2003\n|term_end1    = 21 March 2015\n|predecessor1 = [[Nangolo Mbumba]]\n|successor1   = [[Calle Schlettwein]]\n\n|office2      = Director General of the [[National Planning Commission of Namibia]]\n|president2   = Sam Nujoma\n|term_start2  = 1995\n|term_end2    = 2003\n|predecessor2 = \n|successor2   = [[Immanuel Ngatjizeko]]\n\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1967|10|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Otamanzi Constituency|Otamanzi]], [[South West Africa]] {{small|(now [[Namibia]])}}\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|nationality  = Namibian \n|party        = [[SWAPO]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Lincoln University (Pennsylvania)|Lincoln University]]\n}}\n'''Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila''' (born 12 October 1967) is the fourth and current [[Prime Minister of Namibia]], in office since 21 March 2015. Kuugongelwa-Amadhila is a member of the [[South West Africa People's Organization]] (SWAPO). She has been a member of the [[National Assembly of Namibia]] since 1995 and served as Minister of Finance from 2003 to 2015.<ref name=NID>Graham Hopwood:[http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=101 Who's Who, Kuugongelwa-Amadhila, Saara - Swapo] Namibian Institute for Democracy {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611173411/http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=101 |date=June 11, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"profile\"/> She is the first woman to serve as Prime Minister of Namibia.\n\n==Exile==\nBorn in [[Otamanzi Constituency|Otamanzi]], [[South West Africa]] (present day [[Namibia]]), she went into exile with SWAPO in 1980 at the age of 13 and left for [[Sierra Leone]] in 1982 at the age of 15.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE PRIME MINISTER OF REPUBLIC OF NAMIBIA|url=http://www.opm.gov.na/prime-minister|website=OPM.gov.na|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> She attended [[Koidu Girls Secondary School]] from 1982 to 1984 and Saint Joseph's Secondary School from 1984 to 1987. From 1991 to 1994, she attended [[Lincoln University (Pennsylvania)|Lincoln University]] in [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]], where she graduated with a degree in economics.<ref name=NID/>\n\n==Political career==\nKuugongelwa-Amadhila returned to Namibia following her graduation from Lincoln University and took a position as a desk officer in the Office of the President under President [[Sam Nujoma]]. In 1995, at the age of 27, she was named Director General of the [[National Planning Commission of Namibia|National Planning Commission]], a position in the rank of a minister. She was appointed as Minister of Finance in 2003.<ref name=profile>{{Cite news | title=Profile: Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila | newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]] | date=12 March 2015 | url=https://www.newera.com.na/2015/03/12/profile-saara-kuugongelwa-amadhila/}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Heroes' Day (Namibia)|Heroes' Day]] 2014, she was conferred the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Namibia|Most Brilliant Order of the Sun, Second Class]].<ref>{{Cite news\n|title=Namibians honoured by President\n|newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]\n|date= 28 August 2014\n|url=http://www.newera.com.na/2014/08/28/namibians-honoured-by-president/}}</ref>\n\nAlongside President [[Hage Geingob]], she was sworn in as the 4th Prime Minister of Namibia on 21 March 2015.<ref>Shinovene Immanuel and Theresia Tjihenuna, [http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?id=24731&page_type=story_detail \"Emotional transition\"], ''The Namibian'', 23 March 2015.</ref> She is the first woman to hold the position.<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn May 2016, she took part in \"A Conversation with The Right Honourable Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila, Prime Minister of the Republic of Namibia,\" a moderated discussion with [[Wilson Center]]'s Women in Public Service Project, the Wilson Center Africa Program, and the Constituency for Africa.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Conversation with The Right Honourable Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila, Prime Minister of the Republic of Namibia|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/event/conversation-the-right-honourable-saara-kuugongelwa-amadhila-prime-minister-the-republic|website=WilsonCenter.org|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> She has spoken about gender equality on numerous occasions, including during the [[Mali]] Prime Minister [[Modibo Keita]]'s visit and in a speech (read by Christine Hoebes on her behalf) at the 10th Namibian Women's Summit where she stated that it would take 70 years to close the [[gender pay gap]] across Africa.<ref>{{cite news | title=Gender equity vital to sustained growth | url=https://economist.com.na/18942/general-news/gender-equity-vital-to-sustained-growth/ | newspaper=[[Namibia Economist]] | date=19 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Kahiurika | first=Ndanki | title=70 years to close gender gap \u2013 PM | url=http://www.namibian.com.na/154423/archive-read/70-years-to-close-gender-gap-%E2%80%93-PM | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=15 August 2016 | page=1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hage Geingob]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Namibia]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NamibianPMs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kuugongelwa, Saara}}\n{{Namibia-politician-stub}}\n{{Women-hist-stub}}\n{{econ-policy-stub}} \n{{gender-studies-stub}}\n{{economist-stub}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Lincoln University (Pennsylvania) alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:People from Omusati Region]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Finance Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:SWAPO politicians]]\n[[Category:Women prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Women finance ministers]]\n[[Category:Women economists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Prime Minister of Namibia}}\n{{Expert needed|1=Namibia|ex2=Africa|ex3=Politics|ex4=Economics|reason=An incumbent prime minister, especially if she is the woman to hold the position, should not have this short of an article|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix  = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila\n|honorific-suffix  = MP\n|image        = 2020 Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila.jpg\n|office       = 4th [[Prime Minister of Namibia]]\n|president    = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start   = 21 March 2015\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = Hage Geingob\n|successor    =\n\n|office1      = Minister of Finance\n|president1   = [[Sam Nujoma]]<br/>[[Hifikepunye Pohamba]]<br/>Hage Geingob\n|term_start1  = 2003\n|term_end1    = 21 March 2015\n|predecessor1 = [[Nangolo Mbumba]]\n|successor1   = [[Calle Schlettwein]]\n\n|office2      = Director General of the [[National Planning Commission of Namibia]]\n|president2   = Sam Nujoma\n|term_start2  = 1995\n|term_end2    = 2003\n|predecessor2 = \n|successor2   = [[Immanuel Ngatjizeko]]\n\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1967|10|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Otamanzi Constituency|Otamanzi]], [[South West Africa]] {{small|(now [[Namibia]])}}\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|nationality  = Namibian \n|party        = [[SWAPO]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Lincoln University (Pennsylvania)|Lincoln University]]\n}}\n'''Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila''' (born 12 October 1967) is the fourth and current [[Prime Minister of Namibia]], in office since 21 March 2015. Kuugongelwa-Amadhila is a member of the [[South West Africa People's Organization]] (SWAPO). She has been a member of the [[National Assembly of Namibia]] since 1995 and served as Minister of Finance from 2003 to 2015.<ref name=NID>Graham Hopwood:[http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=101 Who's Who, Kuugongelwa-Amadhila, Saara - Swapo] Namibian Institute for Democracy {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611173411/http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=101 |date=June 11, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"profile\"/> She is the first woman to serve as Prime Minister of Namibia.\n\n==Exile==\nBorn in [[Otamanzi Constituency|Otamanzi]], [[South West Africa]] (Present day [[Namibia]]), she went into exile with SWAPO in 1980 at the age of 13 and left for [[Sierra Leone]] in 1982 at the age of 15.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE PRIME MINISTER OF REPUBLIC OF NAMIBIA|url=http://www.opm.gov.na/prime-minister|website=OPM.gov.na|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> She attended [[Koidu Girls Secondary School]] from 1982 to 1984 and Saint Joseph's Secondary School from 1984 to 1987. From 1991 to 1994, she attended [[Lincoln University (Pennsylvania)|Lincoln University]] in [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]], where she graduated with a degree in economics.<ref name=NID/>\n\n==Political career==\nKuugongelwa-Amadhila returned to Namibia following her graduation from Lincoln University and took a position as a desk officer in the Office of the President under President [[Sam Nujoma]]. In 1995, at the age of 27, she was named Director General of the [[National Planning Commission of Namibia|National Planning Commission]], a position in the rank of a minister. She was appointed as Minister of Finance in 2003.<ref name=profile>{{Cite news | title=Profile: Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila | newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]] | date=12 March 2015 | url=https://www.newera.com.na/2015/03/12/profile-saara-kuugongelwa-amadhila/}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Heroes' Day (Namibia)|Heroes' Day]] 2014, she was conferred the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Namibia|Most Brilliant Order of the Sun, Second Class]].<ref>{{Cite news\n|title=Namibians honoured by President\n|newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]\n|date= 28 August 2014\n|url=http://www.newera.com.na/2014/08/28/namibians-honoured-by-president/}}</ref>\n\nAlongside President [[Hage Geingob]], she was sworn in as the 4th Prime Minister of Namibia on 21 March 2015.<ref>Shinovene Immanuel and Theresia Tjihenuna, [http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?id=24731&page_type=story_detail \"Emotional transition\"], ''The Namibian'', 23 March 2015.</ref> She is the first woman to hold the position.<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn May 2016, she took part in \"A Conversation with The Right Honourable Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila, Prime Minister of the Republic of Namibia,\" a moderated discussion with [[Wilson Center]]'s Women in Public Service Project, the Wilson Center Africa Program, and the Constituency for Africa.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Conversation with The Right Honourable Saara Kuugongelwa-Amadhila, Prime Minister of the Republic of Namibia|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/event/conversation-the-right-honourable-saara-kuugongelwa-amadhila-prime-minister-the-republic|website=WilsonCenter.org|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> She has spoken about gender equality on numerous occasions, including during the [[Mali]] Prime Minister [[Modibo Keita]]'s visit and in a speech (read by Christine Hoebes on her behalf) at the 10th Namibian Women's Summit where she stated that it would take 70 years to close the [[gender pay gap]] across Africa.<ref>{{cite news | title=Gender equity vital to sustained growth | url=https://economist.com.na/18942/general-news/gender-equity-vital-to-sustained-growth/ | newspaper=[[Namibia Economist]] | date=19 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Kahiurika | first=Ndanki | title=70 years to close gender gap \u2013 PM | url=http://www.namibian.com.na/154423/archive-read/70-years-to-close-gender-gap-%E2%80%93-PM | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=15 August 2016 | page=1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hage Geingob]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Namibia]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NamibianPMs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kuugongelwa, Saara}}\n{{Namibia-politician-stub}}\n{{Women-hist-stub}}\n{{econ-policy-stub}} \n{{gender-studies-stub}}\n{{economist-stub}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Lincoln University (Pennsylvania) alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:People from Omusati Region]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Finance Ministers of Namibia]]\n[[Category:SWAPO politicians]]\n[[Category:Women prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Women finance ministers]]\n[[Category:Women economists]]\n", "name_user": "Lihanhendrikse", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saara_Kuugongelwa"}
{"title_page": "Matti Vanhanen", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Vanhanen|Matti Vanhanen's father|Tatu Vanhanen}}\n{{Distinguish|Matti Vanhala}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Matti Vanhanen\n|image          = 2020-03-02 Matti Vanhanen.jpg\n\n|office = [[Speaker of the Parliament of Finland]]\n|term_start = 7 June 2019\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Antti Rinne]]\n|successor = \n|office2         = [[List of Prime Ministers of Finland|40th]] [[Prime Minister of Finland]]\n|president2      = [[Tarja Halonen]]\n|deputy2         = [[Antti Kalliom\u00e4ki]]<br />[[Eero Hein\u00e4luoma]]<br />[[Jyrki Katainen]]\n|term_start2     = 24 June 2003\n|term_end2       = 22 June 2010\n|predecessor2    = [[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]\n|successor2      = [[Mari Kiviniemi]]\n|office3        = [[Minister of Defence (Finland)|Minister of Defence]]\n|primeminister3 = [[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]\n|term_start3    = 17 April 2003\n|term_end3      = 24 June 2003\n|predecessor3   = [[Jan-Erik Enestam]]\n|successor3     = [[Seppo K\u00e4\u00e4ri\u00e4inen]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1955|11|4|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]], [[Central Finland]], [[Finland]]\n|death_date     =\n|death_place    =\n|party          = [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]]\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Merja M\u00e4ntyniemi|1985|2005|end=div}}\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Helsinki]]\n|signature      = Matti Vanhanen Signature 2.svg\n}}\n'''Matti Taneli Vanhanen''' ({{Audio|Fi-Matti_Vanhanen.ogg|pronunciation}}) (born 4 November 1955) is a [[Finland|Finnish]] politician who was [[Prime Minister of Finland]] from 2003 to 2010. He was also Chairman of the [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]], and in the second half of 2006 he was [[President of the European Council]]. In his earlier career he was a journalist. Vanhanen is the son of professor [[Tatu Vanhanen]] and Anni Tiihonen.\n\n==Career==\nVanhanen studied [[political science]] at the [[University of Helsinki]], graduating as a Master of [[Social Science]]s in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valt.helsinki.fi/vol/laitos/alumni/index.htm |title=Yleisen valtio-opin laitos |publisher=Valt.helsinki.fi |date=31 March 2008 |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703051031/http://www.valt.helsinki.fi/vol/laitos/alumni/index.htm |archivedate=3 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was chairman of the Centre Party Youth League from 1980 to 1983. He also served as a member of the [[Espoo]] City Council from 1981 to 1984. Vanhanen used to work as a journalist. He was an editor (1985\u20131988) and editor-in-chief (1988\u20131991) at the local newspaper ''Keh\u00e4sanomat''. In a column in ''[[Suomenmaa]]'' (the Centre Party's organ), he strongly condemned the ''Baltic Star'' pro-Estonian independence demonstration held in Helsinki in July 1985, calling the demonstration \"provocative\".<ref>[http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html Matti Vanhanen, Suomenmaa 30.7.1985 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720185147/http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html |date=20 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nVanhanen was elected to the [[Parliament of Finland|Finnish Parliament (Eduskunta)]] in 1991. As a member of Parliament he was interested in ecological issues. For instance, Vanhanen spoke against the building of a fifth [[nuclear power plant]] in 1992, at the same time as serving on the board of electricity corporation [[Fortum]]. He served on the Parliamentary Environment Committee 1991\u20131995, and was chair of the Parliamentary Grand Committee 2000\u20132001. He was vice-chair of the Centre Party Parliamentary group 1994\u20132001, and Deputy Chairman of the Centre Party 2000\u20132003.\n\nAnother important topic for Vanhanen was [[Foreign relations of Finland|Finland's foreign and security policy]]. As a specialist on the [[European Union]] he was a member of the [[Convention on the Future of Europe|European Union Constitutional Convention]]. There he criticised the president of the convention, former French president [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]], as [[authoritarian]]. Vanhanen has said<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suomenkuvalehti.fi/?id=5835 |title=Suomenkuvalehti.fi |publisher=Suomenkuvalehti.fi |date=12 March 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref> that he is unenthusiastic about European co-operation, and that he is an \"EU pragmatist\", so he may be considered a [[Euroscepticism|eurosceptic]], especially when compared to his EU-enthusiast predecessor [[Paavo Lipponen]].\n\n===Vanhanen's first cabinet===\nVanhanen resigned from the Constitutional Convention in 2003 when he became Minister of Defense in the cabinet of Prime Minister [[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]. After J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki's resignation, Vanhanen [[Matti Vanhanen's first cabinet|was elected Prime Minister]] and [[Matti Vanhanen's first cabinet|his first cabinet]] was formed.\n\nAs a politician, Vanhanen is considered to be part of the liberal wing of the old agrarian Central Party, along with the two other Party ministers from [[Uusimaa|Uusimaa region]]. His government cut the top state income tax rate from 35.5% to 33.5% in 2005 and 32.5% in 2006 (resulting in approximately 55% total tax rate after local government and social security taxes). The corporate tax rate was also lowered to 26% and capital gains to 28% (both formerly 29%), though at the same time dividends were partially made taxable. Vanhanen has said he is willing to continue tax cuts.\n\n===Presidential candidate===\n[[File:World leaders at the 32nd G8 Summit, Strelna, Russia - 20060716.jpg|thumb|right|Vanhanen after [[2006 Finnish presidential election|Finnish 2006 presidential elections]] in G8 Summit in [[Strelna]], Russia. Left to right: [[Romano Prodi]], [[Angela Merkel]], [[Tony Blair]], [[Jacques Chirac]], [[Vladimir Putin]], [[George W. Bush]], [[Junichiro Koizumi]], [[Stephen Harper]], Matti Vanhanen and [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]].]]\nAs the [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]] candidate, Vanhanen challenged [[president of Finland|President]] [[Tarja Halonen]] in the 2006 [[2006 Finnish presidential election|Finnish presidential election]]. He received 18.6% of the vote, coming third to the [[National Coalition Party (Finland)|National Coalition Party]]'s [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] (24.1%) and [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democrat]] and incumbent [[Tarja Halonen]] (46.3%), and thus did not qualify for the runoff. Vanhanen expressed his support for Niinist\u00f6 in the runoff election against his coalition partner's candidate Halonen.\n\nThe presidential election, and co-operation between Centre Party and National Coalition Party, proved to be a major strain on the government coalition between the Centre Party and Social Democrats. The flashpoint came in March, when the Centre Party demanded national [[Agricultural subsidy|agricultural subsidies]] to cover farmers' losses when the Finnish exception in the European Union's [[Common Agricultural Policy]] was about to expire. At the end of the crisis Vanhanen told his parliamentary group that taxpayers would cover ninety percent or about 100 million euros in losses.\n\n===Vanhanen's second cabinet===\n[[File:Vanhasen II hallitus.JPG|thumb|right|350px|Vanhanen's second cabinet.]]\nAfter the [[2007 Finnish parliamentary election|March 2007 election]] the Centre Party narrowly remained the largest party after losing four seats. However their coalition partner, the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|SDP]], lost eight seats and the centre-right [[National Coalition Party (Finland)|National Coalition Party]] gained ten. [[Matti Vanhanen's second cabinet|Vanhanen's second cabinet]] was formed on a centre-right basis, with minor partners the [[Green League]] and the [[Swedish People's Party (Finland)|Swedish People's Party]].\n\nA scandal involving Vanhanen's second cabinet began rolling in May 2008, after the leader of the Centre Party's parliamentary group [[Timo Kalli]] said publicly that he would not reveal information about his [[campaign finance]]s, because such disclosure was not required. After a media backlash, Kalli gave up his secrecy and listed a group of businessmen known as \"Kehittyvien maakuntien Suomi\" (KMS; in English, \"The Finland of Developing Regions\"), who had financed the Centre Party. Centre Party links with KMS were suspected, as one address of the organisation belonged to a party official. It was later revealed that the organisation had been formed in the Centre Party's general secretary's office.\n\nAfter the Russian response to the Georgian invasion of South Ossetia, Vanhanen said that Finland would rethink its security.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/news/2008/08/vanhanen_finland_to_rethink_security_following_crisis_in_georgia_314968.html |title=Vanhanen: Finland to Rethink Security Following Crisis in Georgia |publisher=Yle.fi |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229204507/http://yle.fi/uutiset/news/2008/08/vanhanen_finland_to_rethink_security_following_crisis_in_georgia_314968.html |archivedate=29 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nVanhanen's cabinet proposed raising the retirement age from 63 to 65 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/200902289164604_uu.shtml |title=Vanhanen: El\u00e4kei\u00e4n korotus l\u00e4hti minun aloitteestani |publisher=Iltalehti.fi |date=28 February 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/kotimaa.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2009/02/818706 |title=Vanhanen: El\u00e4kei\u00e4n nostolla maksetaan laman laskut |publisher=Mtv3.fi |date=25 February 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/3-5730671 |title=PM Vanhanen: \"Necessary to Raise Pension Age\" |publisher=Yle.fi |date=8 March 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23 }}</ref> His proposal was fiercely opposed by the [[Central Organisation of Finnish Trade Unions]] (Finnish acronym SAK), which is affiliated with the SDP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taloussanomat.fi/tyomarkkinat/2009/03/02/sak--uhkaa-katkaista-valit-hallitukseen/20095555/12 |title=SAK uhkaa katkaista v\u00e4lit hallitukseen |publisher=Taloussanomat.fi |date=3 February 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, Vanhanen announced that he would step down as chair of the Centre Party at its June 2010 convention. [[Mari Kiviniemi]] was chosen to the position and she also inherited the position as Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/mari_kiviniemi_wins_centre_chair_taking_over_as_pm/1755712 |title=Mari Kiviniemi Wins Centre Chair, Taking Over as PM |publisher=Yle |date=12 June 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> In September 2010 Vanhanen started as the head of the Family Business Network Finland and left the parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kaleva.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/vanhasesta-perheyritysten-liiton-toimitusjohtaja/173795/ |title=Vanhasesta Perheyritysten liiton toimitusjohtaja |publisher=Kaleva |date=23 June 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the Finnish police investigated whether Vanhanen had been wrong not to disqualify himself in certain cabinet decisions on financial contributions to an organisation affiliated with the Centre Party, which had previously financed Vanhanen's presidential campaign. Because the charges concerned Vanhanen's actions while in office, the decision whether he should be prosecuted fell to the Constitutional Law Committee of the [[Finnish Parliament]]. The Committee decided not to prosecute Vanhanen.\n\n===Return to politics===\nIn November 2014, Vanhanen announced that he would leave the Family Business Network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-1288773672340.html |title=Matti Vanhanen paljastaa, mik\u00e4 veti takaisin politiikkaan |work=Ilta-Sanomat |date=18 November 2014 |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> He was elected to the parliament in the 2015 elections with 11,304 personal votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E-2015/fi/kokomaaval.html |title=Valitut ehdokkaat Koko maa |publisher=Ministry of Justice |date=22 April 2015 |accessdate=9 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625063910/http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E-2015/fi/kokomaaval.html |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In June 2015, Vanhanen was chosen as the chairman of the Centre Party parliamentary group.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/a1433209210056 |title=Matti Vanhanen valittiin keskustan eduskuntaryhm\u00e4n puheenjohtajaksi |work=Helsingin Sanomat |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Vanhanen announced that he is seeking Centre Party's candidacy in 2018 [[2018 Finnish presidential election|presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/a1458188578788?ref=hs-prio-4-3 |title=Vanhanen l\u00e4htee presidenttikisaan ja luopuu keskustan eduskuntaryhm\u00e4n johdosta |publisher=Helsingin sanomat |date=17 March 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2016 |language=Finnish}}</ref><ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/vanhanenpresidentiksi/ Matti Vanhanen presidentiksi] (in Finnish). Retrieved 2016-05-21.</ref> As no challengers appeared within the party, Vanhanen was the sole candidate in June's party conference and was confirmed as the Centre Party's candidate in the presidential election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/kotimaa/a1462936635076 |title=Matti Vanhasesta keskustan presidenttiehdokas \u2013 kukaan ei ilmoittautunut haastajaksi |publisher=Helsingin sanomat |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate=11 May 2016 |language=Finnish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2016061221714870_uu.shtml |title=Matti Vanhasesta yksimielisesti keskustan presidenttiehdokas |publisher=Iltalehti |date=12 June 2016 |accessdate=12 June 2016 |language=Finnish}}</ref> Vanhanen said that his candidacy is motivated by the support he felt he had around the country during his last campaign and the will to improve the security situation in the areas surrounding Finland.<ref>[http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000001140341.html Matti Vanhanen kertoo nyt, miksi h\u00e4n haluaa Suomen presidentiksi] (in Finnish). ''Ilta Sanomat''. Retrieved 2016-05-21.</ref> Following the nomination, Vanhanen left his duties as the chairman of the parliamentary group in order to focus on global affairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/matti_vanhanen_luopuu_eduskuntaryhman_puheenjohtajuudesta_keskittyy_presidenttiehdokkuuteen/8751213 |title=Matti Vanhanen luopuu eduskuntaryhm\u00e4n puheenjohtajuudesta, keskittyy presidenttiehdokkuuteen |publisher=Yle |date=7 March 2016 |accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref> On 23 June 2016, Vanhanen was chosen as the chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee in the Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suomenmaa.fi/?app=NeoDirect&com=6/3/127379/88fc63148a |title=Matti Vanhanen yksimielisesti ulkoasiainvaliokunnan puheenjohtajaksi |publisher=Suomenmaa |date=23 June 2016 |accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref> In the first round of the presidential election, Vanhanen placed fifth with 4.1 percent of the votes, while the incumbent president [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] went on to secure his second term with a majority of votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/TPV-2018_1/fi/ehdtulos_kokomaa.html |title=Presidentinvaali 2018, 1. vaali: Ehdokkaiden \u00e4\u00e4net|publisher=Ministry of Justice|date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=29 January 2018 |language=Finnish}}</ref>\n\n==Personality==\n[[File:Nordic Prime Ministers 2010.jpg|thumb|right|350px|The Nordic prime ministers meeting in Denmark, 2010. From left to right: Fredrik Reinfeldt (Sweden), Jens Stoltenberg (Norway), J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir (Iceland), Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen (Denmark), Matti Vanhanen (Finland).]]\n[[File:Lula-Vanhanen-15-05-2008.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Vanhanen and the 35th President of Brazil [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]].]]\nVanhanen has been characterised as [[charisma|uncharismatic]] and even boring, which he has attempted to turn to his advantage in tense political situations. Vanhanen is known for being a [[teetotalism|teetotaler]], saying that he does not like the taste of alcohol.<ref>{{cite web|author=taz, die tageszeitung |url=http://www.taz.de/pt/2003/06/25/a0148.nf/text |title=Archiv |publisher=taz.de |date= |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nMatti Vanhanen was against the independence movement in the [[Baltic States]] during the 1980s. In his column in Suomenmaa in 1985, Vanhanen condemned the Baltic independence movement both for \"wishing to change the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] system\" and for \"indifference towards the post [[Second World War]] reality.\" Vanhanen claimed that the difference between capitalism and socialism was not significant; and that instead of being concerned about the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] system, it would be better to concentrate, for example, on the research of [[Finno-Ugric languages]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html |title=Matti Vanhanen, Suomenmaa 30.7.1985 |publisher=Kavkaz.fi |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720185147/http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html |archivedate=20 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he visited [[People's Republic of China|China]] and credited the government for being [[:wikt:systematic|systematic]], as well as being able to place clear priorities and to mobilise the required resources to accomplish them. In his opinion, the Western world ought to note the example of China, where policies are implemented rapidly and effectively.<ref>{{cite web|author=Petteri Tuohinen |url=http://www.hs.fi/artikkeli/Vanhanen+L%C3%A4nsimaat+voisivat+ottaa+oppia+Kiinasta+tehokkuudessa/1135245327236 |title=Petteri Tuohinen \u2018Vanhanen: Lansimaat voisivat ottaa oppia Kiinan tehokkuudesta\u2019 Helsingin Sanomat 21.4.2009 |publisher=Hs.fi |date=21 April 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref> He said he was impressed of the progress the country has made in dealing with difficult issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/China+smothers+Vanhanen+in+cordial+language/1135219742524 |title=China smothers Vanhanen in cordial language 29.4.2009 |publisher=Hs.fi |date= |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nVanhanen married Merja Vanhanen in 1985. They have two children: Annastiina (born 1991) and Juhana (born 1994). Matti Vanhanen and Merja Vanhanen unexpectedly announced their divorce on 6 April 2005.\n\nAfter his divorce, he dated [[Susan Kuronen]] (she later changed her last name to Ruusunen).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/viihde/200607314940634_vi.shtml |title=Viihde &#124; 01.08.2006 &#124; Matti Vanhanen ja Susan viihtyv\u00e4t yhdess\u00e4 |publisher=Iltalehti.fi |date=8 January 2006 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Susan+speaks+now+-+but+not+in+an+exclusive+interview/1135223472440 |title=Helsingin Sanomat \u2013 International Edition \u2013 People |publisher=Hs.fi |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522031057/http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Susan+speaks+now+-+but+not+in+an+exclusive+interview/1135223472440 |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In February 2007, Kuronen released a tell-all book ''The Prime Minister's Bride'', which actually boosted the prime minister's popularity with the public. Tens of thousands of Finns signed an online petition against the book and some bookstores refused to put it on the shelf.<ref>http://apnews.myway.com/article/20070315/D8NSNU780.html</ref> Vanhanen sued the book's publisher (but not Kuronen) for invasion of privacy in March 2007, following the March elections. In 2010 the [[Supreme Court of Finland]] upheld the privacy violation conviction against Susan Ruusunen and her publisher.<ref>[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Supreme+Court+upholds+privacy+violation+conviction+against+Susan+Ruusunen+and+publisher+for+kiss-and-tell+book/1135257623302 Supreme Court upholds privacy violation conviction against Susan Ruusunen and publisher for kiss-and-tell book] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610120934/http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Supreme+Court+upholds+privacy+violation+conviction+against+Susan+Ruusunen+and+publisher+for+kiss-and-tell+book/1135257623302 |date=10 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter ending his dating relationship with Kuronen (Ruusunen), Vanhanen got engaged to Sirkka Mertala in 2009. This relationship ended in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/artikkeli/IS+Vanhanen+ja+Mertala+erosivat/1135258640912 |title=Helsingin Sanomat |publisher=hs.fi |accessdate=2010-07-22 |language=fi |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720044617/http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/artikkeli/IS+Vanhanen+ja+Mertala+erosivat/1135258640912 |archivedate=20 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 book commissioned for the presidential elections, ''Se on ihan Matti'', Vanhanen compared the Finnish [[tabloid press]] to the [[KGB]] and [[Stasi]], former [[Soviet Union]] and [[East Germany|East German]] secret police agencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/kotimaa.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2005/10/400901 |title=MTV3 Internet >Uutiset \u2013 Kotimaa |publisher=Mtv3.fi |date=21 October 2005 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nVanhanen is about 198&nbsp;cm (6'6\"). He is [[left-handed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/picture/1101981916452 |title=Helsingin Sanomat \u2013 International Edition |publisher=Hs.fi |date= |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign funds==\n{{See also| Corruption in Finland}}\nMatti Vanhanen received 25,000 euros for his presidential election campaign in 2006 from [[Ahti Vilppula]] via his company Helsingin Mekaanikkotalo. Mekaanikkotalo is owned by Procomex in [[Luxembourg]] and further by Kilbrin Investments Limited in the [[Virgin Islands]].<ref>Matti Yl\u00f6nen Veroparatiisit, 20 ratkaisua varjotalouteen Like 2008 page 108 {{in lang|fi}}</ref> In 2009 it was found out that this finance was not included in the finance announcement. Also [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] had not announced his finance 50,000 \u20ac from Ahti Vilppula in 2006 by 2009.<ref>Helsingin Sanomat 17 September 2009 A4</ref>\n\n== Youth Foundation ==\n{{See also| 2007 Finnish campaign finance scandal}}\nVanhanen served as Chairman of the Youth Foundation from 1998 to 2003 and Deputy chairman from 1981 to 1997. The prosecution claims the Youth Foundation donated under the direction of Centre Party MP Antti Kaikkonen funding of over 90,000 euros for his own campaign and that of other Centre Party MPs including Matti Vanhanen. Prosecutors say this contravened the Foundation's own rules and laws governing such institutions.<ref>[http://yle.fi/uutiset/vanhanen_no_talk_of_campaign_funding_in_youth_foundation/6330074 Vanhanen: No talk of campaign funding in Youth Foundation, Former Prime Minister Matti Vanhanen took the witness stand today in the trial of former leaders of the Youth Foundation] yle 10 October 2012</ref>\n\n==Cabinets==\n* [[Vanhanen I Cabinet]]\n* [[Vanhanen II Cabinet]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Keskusta]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Matti Vanhanen}}\n* {{in lang|fi}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20090309040909/http://www.keskusta.fi/Suomeksi/Matti.iw3 Official site]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jan-Erik Enestam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (Finland)|Minister of Defence]]|years=2003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seppo K\u00e4\u00e4ri\u00e4inen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=2003\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mari Kiviniemi]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Antti Rinne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the Parliament of Finland|Speaker of Parliament]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Wolfgang Sch\u00fcssel]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the European Council]]|years=2006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Angela Merkel]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FinnishPrimeMinisters}}\n{{CentrePartyFinlandLeaders}}\n{{Presidents of the European Council}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vanhanen, Matti}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]]\n[[Category:Centre Party (Finland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Defence of Finland]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Parliament of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1991\u201395)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1995\u201399)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1999\u20132003)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2003\u201307)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2007\u201311)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2015\u201319)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2019\u201323)]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Finland]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the European Council]]\n[[Category:Finnish bloggers]]\n[[Category:University of Helsinki alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Vanhanen|Matti Vanhanen's father|Tatu Vanhanen}}\n{{Distinguish|Matti Vanhala}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Matti Vanhanen\n|image          = 2020-03-02 Matti Vanhanen.jpg\n\n|office = [[Speaker of the Parliament of Finland]]\n|term_start = 7 June 2019\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Antti Rinne]]\n|successor = \n|office2         = [[List of Prime Ministers of Finland|40th]] [[Prime Minister of Finland]]\n|president2      = [[Tarja Halonen]]\n|deputy2         = [[Antti Kalliom\u00e4ki]]<br />[[Eero Hein\u00e4luoma]]<br />[[Jyrki Katainen]]\n|term_start2     = 24 June 2003\n|term_end2       = 22 June 2010\n|predecessor2    = [[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]\n|successor2      = [[Mari Kiviniemi]]\n|office3        = [[Minister of Defence (Finland)|Minister of Defence]]\n|primeminister3 = [[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]\n|term_start3    = 17 April 2003\n|term_end3      = 24 June 2003\n|predecessor3   = [[Jan-Erik Enestam]]\n|successor3     = [[Seppo K\u00e4\u00e4ri\u00e4inen]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1955|11|4|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]], [[Central Finland]], [[Finland]]\n|death_date     =\n|death_place    =\n|party          = [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]]\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Merja M\u00e4ntyniemi|1985|2005|end=div}}\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Helsinki]]\n|signature      = Matti Vanhanen Signature 2.svg\n}}\n'''Matti Taneli Vanhanen''' ({{Audio|Fi-Matti_Vanhanen.ogg|pronunciation}}) (born 4 November 1955) is a [[Finland|Finnish]] politician who was [[Prime Minister of Finland]] from 2003 to 2010. He was also Chairman of the [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]], and in the second half of 2006 he was [[President of the European Council]]. In his earlier career he was a journalist. Vanhanen is the son of professor [[Tatu Vanhanen]] and Anni Tiihonen.\n\n==Career==\nVanhanen studied [[political science]] at the [[University of Helsinki]], graduating as a Master of [[Social Science]]s in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valt.helsinki.fi/vol/laitos/alumni/index.htm |title=Yleisen valtio-opin laitos |publisher=Valt.helsinki.fi |date=31 March 2008 |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703051031/http://www.valt.helsinki.fi/vol/laitos/alumni/index.htm |archivedate=3 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was chairman of the Centre Party Youth League from 1980 to 1983. He also served as a member of the [[Espoo]] City Council from 1981 to 1984. Vanhanen used to work as a journalist. He was an editor (1985\u20131988) and editor-in-chief (1988\u20131991) at the local newspaper ''Keh\u00e4sanomat''. In a column in ''[[Suomenmaa]]'' (the Centre Party's organ), he strongly condemned the ''Baltic Star'' pro-Estonian independence demonstration held in Helsinki in July 1985, calling the demonstration \"provocative\".<ref>[http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html Matti Vanhanen, Suomenmaa 30.7.1985 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720185147/http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html |date=20 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nVanhanen was elected to the [[Parliament of Finland|Finnish Parliament (Eduskunta)]] in 1991. As a member of Parliament he was interested in ecological issues. For instance, Vanhanen spoke against the building of a fifth [[nuclear power plant]] in 1992, at the same time as serving on the board of electricity corporation [[Fortum]]. He served on the Parliamentary Environment Committee 1991\u20131995, and was chair of the Parliamentary Grand Committee 2000\u20132001. He was vice-chair of the Centre Party Parliamentary group 1994\u20132001, and Deputy Chairman of the Centre Party 2000\u20132003.\n\nAnother important topic for Vanhanen was [[Foreign relations of Finland|Finland's foreign and security policy]]. As a specialist on the [[European Union]] he was a member of the [[Convention on the Future of Europe|European Union Constitutional Convention]]. There he criticised the president of the convention, former French president [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]], as [[authoritarian]]. Vanhanen has said<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suomenkuvalehti.fi/?id=5835 |title=Suomenkuvalehti.fi |publisher=Suomenkuvalehti.fi |date=12 March 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref> that he is unenthusiastic about European co-operation, and that he is an \"EU pragmatist\", so he may be considered a [[Euroscepticism|eurosceptic]], especially when compared to his EU-enthusiast predecessor [[Paavo Lipponen]].\n\n===Vanhanen's first cabinet===\nVanhanen resigned from the Constitutional Convention in 2003 when he became Minister of Defense in the cabinet of Prime Minister [[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]. After J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki's resignation, Vanhanen [[Matti Vanhanen's first cabinet|was elected Prime Minister]] and [[Matti Vanhanen's first cabinet|his first cabinet]] was formed.\n\nAs a politician, Vanhanen is considered to be part of the liberal wing of the old agrarian Central Party, along with the two other Party ministers from [[Uusimaa|Uusimaa region]]. His government cut the top state income tax rate from 35.5% to 33.5% in 2005 and 32.5% in 2006 (resulting in approximately 55% total tax rate after local government and social security taxes). The corporate tax rate was also lowered to 26% and capital gains to 28% (both formerly 29%), though at the same time dividends were partially made taxable. Vanhanen has said he is willing to continue tax cuts.\n\n===Presidential candidate===\n[[File:World leaders at the 32nd G8 Summit, Strelna, Russia - 20060716.jpg|thumb|right|Vanhanen after [[2006 Finnish presidential election|Finnish 2006 presidential elections]] in G8 Summit in [[Strelna]], Russia. Left to right: [[Romano Prodi]], [[Angela Merkel]], [[Tony Blair]], [[Jacques Chirac]], [[Vladimir Putin]], [[George W. Bush]], [[Junichiro Koizumi]], [[Stephen Harper]], Matti Vanhanen and [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]].]]\nAs the [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]] candidate, Vanhanen challenged [[president of Finland|President]] [[Tarja Halonen]] in the 2006 [[2006 Finnish presidential election|Finnish presidential election]]. He received 18.6% of the vote, coming third to the [[National Coalition Party (Finland)|National Coalition Party]]'s [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] (24.1%) and [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democrat]] and incumbent [[Tarja Halonen]] (46.3%), and thus did not qualify for the runoff. Vanhanen expressed his support for Niinist\u00f6 in the runoff election against his coalition partner's candidate Halonen.\n\nThe presidential election, and co-operation between Centre Party and National Coalition Party, proved to be a major strain on the government coalition between the Centre Party and Social Democrats. The flashpoint came in March, when the Centre Party demanded national [[Agricultural subsidy|agricultural subsidies]] to cover farmers' losses when the Finnish exception in the European Union's [[Common Agricultural Policy]] was about to expire. At the end of the crisis Vanhanen told his parliamentary group that taxpayers would cover ninety percent or about 100 million euros in losses.\n\n===Vanhanen's second cabinet===\n[[File:Vanhasen II hallitus.JPG|thumb|right|350px|Vanhanen's second cabinet.]]\nAfter the [[2007 Finnish parliamentary election|March 2007 election]] the Centre Party narrowly remained the largest party after losing four seats. However their coalition partner, the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|SDP]], lost eight seats and the centre-right [[National Coalition Party (Finland)|National Coalition Party]] gained ten. [[Matti Vanhanen's second cabinet|Vanhanen's second cabinet]] was formed on a centre-right basis, with minor partners the [[Green League]] and the [[Swedish People's Party (Finland)|Swedish People's Party]].\n\nA scandal involving Vanhanen's second cabinet began rolling in May 2008, after the leader of the Centre Party's parliamentary group [[Timo Kalli]] said publicly that he would not reveal information about his [[campaign finance]]s, because such disclosure was not required. After a media backlash, Kalli gave up his secrecy and listed a group of businessmen known as \"Kehittyvien maakuntien Suomi\" (KMS; in English, \"The Finland of Developing Regions\"), who had financed the Centre Party. Centre Party links with KMS were suspected, as one address of the organisation belonged to a party official. It was later revealed that the organisation had been formed in the Centre Party's general secretary's office.\n\nAfter the Russian response to the Georgian invasion of South Ossetia, Vanhanen said that Finland would rethink its security.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/news/2008/08/vanhanen_finland_to_rethink_security_following_crisis_in_georgia_314968.html |title=Vanhanen: Finland to Rethink Security Following Crisis in Georgia |publisher=Yle.fi |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229204507/http://yle.fi/uutiset/news/2008/08/vanhanen_finland_to_rethink_security_following_crisis_in_georgia_314968.html |archivedate=29 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nVanhanen's cabinet proposed raising the retirement age from 63 to 65 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/200902289164604_uu.shtml |title=Vanhanen: El\u00e4kei\u00e4n korotus l\u00e4hti minun aloitteestani |publisher=Iltalehti.fi |date=28 February 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/kotimaa.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2009/02/818706 |title=Vanhanen: El\u00e4kei\u00e4n nostolla maksetaan laman laskut |publisher=Mtv3.fi |date=25 February 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/3-5730671 |title=PM Vanhanen: \"Necessary to Raise Pension Age\" |publisher=Yle.fi |date=8 March 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23 }}</ref> His proposal was fiercely opposed by the [[Central Organisation of Finnish Trade Unions]] (Finnish acronym SAK), which is affiliated with the SDP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taloussanomat.fi/tyomarkkinat/2009/03/02/sak--uhkaa-katkaista-valit-hallitukseen/20095555/12 |title=SAK uhkaa katkaista v\u00e4lit hallitukseen |publisher=Taloussanomat.fi |date=3 February 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, Vanhanen announced that he would step down as chair of the Centre Party at its June 2010 convention. [[Mari Kiviniemi]] was chosen to the position and she also inherited the position as Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/mari_kiviniemi_wins_centre_chair_taking_over_as_pm/1755712 |title=Mari Kiviniemi Wins Centre Chair, Taking Over as PM |publisher=Yle |date=12 June 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> In September 2010 Vanhanen started as the head of the Family Business Network Finland and left the parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kaleva.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/vanhasesta-perheyritysten-liiton-toimitusjohtaja/173795/ |title=Vanhasesta Perheyritysten liiton toimitusjohtaja |publisher=Kaleva |date=23 June 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the Finnish police investigated whether Vanhanen had been wrong not to disqualify himself in certain cabinet decisions on financial contributions to an organisation affiliated with the Centre Party, which had previously financed Vanhanen's presidential campaign. Because the charges concerned Vanhanen's actions while in office, the decision whether he should be prosecuted fell to the Constitutional Law Committee of the [[Finnish Parliament]]. The Committee decided not to prosecute Vanhanen.\n\n===Return to politics===\nIn November 2014, Vanhanen announced that he would leave the Family Business Network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-1288773672340.html |title=Matti Vanhanen paljastaa, mik\u00e4 veti takaisin politiikkaan |work=Ilta-Sanomat |date=18 November 2014 |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> He was elected to the parliament in the 2015 elections with 11,304 personal votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E-2015/fi/kokomaaval.html |title=Valitut ehdokkaat Koko maa |publisher=Ministry of Justice |date=22 April 2015 |accessdate=9 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625063910/http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E-2015/fi/kokomaaval.html |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In June 2015, Vanhanen was chosen as the chairman of the Centre Party parliamentary group.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/a1433209210056 |title=Matti Vanhanen valittiin keskustan eduskuntaryhm\u00e4n puheenjohtajaksi |work=Helsingin Sanomat |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Vanhanen announced that he is seeking Centre Party's candidacy in 2018 [[2018 Finnish presidential election|presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/a1458188578788?ref=hs-prio-4-3 |title=Vanhanen l\u00e4htee presidenttikisaan ja luopuu keskustan eduskuntaryhm\u00e4n johdosta |publisher=Helsingin sanomat |date=17 March 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2016 |language=Finnish}}</ref><ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/vanhanenpresidentiksi/ Matti Vanhanen presidentiksi] (in Finnish). Retrieved 2016-05-21.</ref> As no challengers appeared within the party, Vanhanen was the sole candidate in June's party conference and was confirmed as the Centre Party's candidate in the presidential election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/kotimaa/a1462936635076 |title=Matti Vanhasesta keskustan presidenttiehdokas \u2013 kukaan ei ilmoittautunut haastajaksi |publisher=Helsingin sanomat |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate=11 May 2016 |language=Finnish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2016061221714870_uu.shtml |title=Matti Vanhasesta yksimielisesti keskustan presidenttiehdokas |publisher=Iltalehti |date=12 June 2016 |accessdate=12 June 2016 |language=Finnish}}</ref> Vanhanen said that his candidacy is motivated by the support he felt he had around the country during his last campaign and the will to improve the security situation in the areas surrounding Finland.<ref>[http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000001140341.html Matti Vanhanen kertoo nyt, miksi h\u00e4n haluaa Suomen presidentiksi] (in Finnish). ''Ilta Sanomat''. Retrieved 2016-05-21.</ref> Following the nomination, Vanhanen left his duties as the chairman of the parliamentary group in order to focus on global affairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/matti_vanhanen_luopuu_eduskuntaryhman_puheenjohtajuudesta_keskittyy_presidenttiehdokkuuteen/8751213 |title=Matti Vanhanen luopuu eduskuntaryhm\u00e4n puheenjohtajuudesta, keskittyy presidenttiehdokkuuteen |publisher=Yle |date=7 March 2016 |accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref> On 23 June 2016, Vanhanen was chosen as the chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee in the Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suomenmaa.fi/?app=NeoDirect&com=6/3/127379/88fc63148a |title=Matti Vanhanen yksimielisesti ulkoasiainvaliokunnan puheenjohtajaksi |publisher=Suomenmaa |date=23 June 2016 |accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref> In the first round of the presidential election, Vanhanen placed fifth with 4.1 percent of the votes, while the incumbent president [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] went on to secure his second term with a majority of votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/TPV-2018_1/fi/ehdtulos_kokomaa.html |title=Presidentinvaali 2018, 1. vaali: Ehdokkaiden \u00e4\u00e4net|publisher=Ministry of Justice|date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=29 January 2018 |language=Finnish}}</ref>\n\n==Personality==\n[[File:Nordic Prime Ministers 2010.jpg|thumb|right|350px|The Nordic prime ministers meeting in Denmark, 2010. From left to right: Fredrik Reinfeldt (Sweden), Jens Stoltenberg (Norway), J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir (Iceland), Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen (Denmark), Matti Vanhanen (Finland).]]\n[[File:Lula-Vanhanen-15-05-2008.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Vanhanen and the 35th President of Brazil [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]].]]\nVanhanen has been characterised as [[charisma|uncharismatic]] and even boring, which he has attempted to turn to his advantage in tense political situations. Vanhanen is known for being a [[teetotalism|teetotaler]], saying that he does not like the taste of alcohol.<ref>{{cite web|author=taz, die tageszeitung |url=http://www.taz.de/pt/2003/06/25/a0148.nf/text |title=Archiv |publisher=taz.de |date= |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nMatti Vanhanen was against the independence movement in the [[Baltic States]] during the 1980s. In his column in Suomenmaa in 1985, Vanhanen condemned the Baltic independence movement both for \"wishing to change the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] system\" and for \"indifference towards the post [[Second World War]] reality.\" Vanhanen claimed that the difference between capitalism and socialism was not significant; and that instead of being concerned about the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] system, it would be better to concentrate, for example, on the research of [[Finno-Ugric languages]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html |title=Matti Vanhanen, Suomenmaa 30.7.1985 |publisher=Kavkaz.fi |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720185147/http://kavkaz.fi/vanhanen.html |archivedate=20 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he visited [[People's Republic of China|China]] and credited the government for being [[:wikt:systematic|systematic]], as well as being able to place clear priorities and to mobilise the required resources to accomplish them. In his opinion, the Western world ought to note the example of China, where policies are implemented rapidly and effectively.<ref>{{cite web|author=Petteri Tuohinen |url=http://www.hs.fi/artikkeli/Vanhanen+L%C3%A4nsimaat+voisivat+ottaa+oppia+Kiinasta+tehokkuudessa/1135245327236 |title=Petteri Tuohinen \u2018Vanhanen: Lansimaat voisivat ottaa oppia Kiinan tehokkuudesta\u2019 Helsingin Sanomat 21.4.2009 |publisher=Hs.fi |date=21 April 2009 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref> He said he was impressed of the progress the country has made in dealing with difficult issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/China+smothers+Vanhanen+in+cordial+language/1135219742524 |title=China smothers Vanhanen in cordial language 29.4.2009 |publisher=Hs.fi |date= |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nVanhanen married Merja Vanhanen in 1985. They have two children: Annastiina (born 1991) and Juhana (born 1994). Matti Vanhanen and Merja Vanhanen unexpectedly announced their divorce on 6 April 2005.\n\nAfter his divorce, he dated [[Susan Kuronen]] (she later changed her last name to Ruusunen).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/viihde/200607314940634_vi.shtml |title=Viihde &#124; 01.08.2006 &#124; Matti Vanhanen ja Susan viihtyv\u00e4t yhdess\u00e4 |publisher=Iltalehti.fi |date=8 January 2006 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Susan+speaks+now+-+but+not+in+an+exclusive+interview/1135223472440 |title=Helsingin Sanomat \u2013 International Edition \u2013 People |publisher=Hs.fi |accessdate=2010-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522031057/http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Susan+speaks+now+-+but+not+in+an+exclusive+interview/1135223472440 |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In February 2007, Kuronen released a tell-all book ''The Prime Minister's Bride'', which actually boosted the prime minister's popularity with the public. Tens of thousands of Finns signed an online petition against the book and some bookstores refused to put it on the shelf.<ref>http://apnews.myway.com/article/20070315/D8NSNU780.html</ref> Vanhanen sued the book\u00b4s publisher (but not Kuronen) for invasion of privacy in March 2007, following the March elections. In 2010 the [[Supreme Court of Finland]] upheld the privacy violation conviction against Susan Ruusunen and her publisher.<ref>[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Supreme+Court+upholds+privacy+violation+conviction+against+Susan+Ruusunen+and+publisher+for+kiss-and-tell+book/1135257623302 Supreme Court upholds privacy violation conviction against Susan Ruusunen and publisher for kiss-and-tell book] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610120934/http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Supreme+Court+upholds+privacy+violation+conviction+against+Susan+Ruusunen+and+publisher+for+kiss-and-tell+book/1135257623302 |date=10 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter ending his dating relationship with Kuronen (Ruusunen), Vanhanen got engaged to Sirkka Mertala in 2009. This relationship ended in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/artikkeli/IS+Vanhanen+ja+Mertala+erosivat/1135258640912 |title=Helsingin Sanomat |publisher=hs.fi |accessdate=2010-07-22 |language=fi |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720044617/http://www.hs.fi/politiikka/artikkeli/IS+Vanhanen+ja+Mertala+erosivat/1135258640912 |archivedate=20 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 book commissioned for the presidential elections, ''Se on ihan Matti'', Vanhanen compared the Finnish [[tabloid press]] to the [[KGB]] and [[Stasi]], former [[Soviet Union]] and [[East Germany|East German]] secret police agencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/kotimaa.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2005/10/400901 |title=MTV3 Internet >Uutiset \u2013 Kotimaa |publisher=Mtv3.fi |date=21 October 2005 |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\nVanhanen is about 198&nbsp;cm (6'6\"). He is [[left-handed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/picture/1101981916452 |title=Helsingin Sanomat \u2013 International Edition |publisher=Hs.fi |date= |accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign funds==\n{{See also| Corruption in Finland}}\nMatti Vanhanen received 25,000 euros for his presidential election campaign in 2006 from [[Ahti Vilppula]] via his company Helsingin Mekaanikkotalo. Mekaanikkotalo is owned by Procomex in [[Luxembourg]] and further by Kilbrin Investments Limited in the [[Virgin Islands]].<ref>Matti Yl\u00f6nen Veroparatiisit, 20 ratkaisua varjotalouteen Like 2008 page 108 {{in lang|fi}}</ref> In 2009 it was found out that this finance was not included in the finance announcement. Also [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] had not announced his finance 50,000 \u20ac from Ahti Vilppula in 2006 by 2009.<ref>Helsingin Sanomat 17 September 2009 A4</ref>\n\n== Youth Foundation ==\n{{See also| 2007 Finnish campaign finance scandal}}\nVanhanen served as Chairman of the Youth Foundation from 1998 to 2003 and Deputy chairman from 1981 to 1997. The prosecution claims the Youth Foundation donated under the direction of Centre Party MP Antti Kaikkonen funding of over 90,000 euros for his own campaign and that of other Centre Party MPs including Matti Vanhanen. Prosecutors say this contravened the Foundation's own rules and laws governing such institutions.<ref>[http://yle.fi/uutiset/vanhanen_no_talk_of_campaign_funding_in_youth_foundation/6330074 Vanhanen: No talk of campaign funding in Youth Foundation, Former Prime Minister Matti Vanhanen took the witness stand today in the trial of former leaders of the Youth Foundation] yle 10 October 2012</ref>\n\n==Cabinets==\n* [[Vanhanen I Cabinet]]\n* [[Vanhanen II Cabinet]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Keskusta]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Matti Vanhanen}}\n* {{in lang|fi}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20090309040909/http://www.keskusta.fi/Suomeksi/Matti.iw3 Official site]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jan-Erik Enestam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (Finland)|Minister of Defence]]|years=2003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seppo K\u00e4\u00e4ri\u00e4inen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anneli J\u00e4\u00e4tteenm\u00e4ki]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=2003\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mari Kiviniemi]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Antti Rinne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the Parliament of Finland|Speaker of Parliament]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Wolfgang Sch\u00fcssel]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the European Council]]|years=2006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Angela Merkel]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FinnishPrimeMinisters}}\n{{CentrePartyFinlandLeaders}}\n{{Presidents of the European Council}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vanhanen, Matti}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]]\n[[Category:Centre Party (Finland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Defence of Finland]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Parliament of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1991\u201395)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1995\u201399)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1999\u20132003)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2003\u201307)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2007\u201311)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2015\u201319)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2019\u201323)]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Finland]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the European Council]]\n[[Category:Finnish bloggers]]\n[[Category:University of Helsinki alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonality:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u00b4s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matti_Vanhanen"}
{"title_page": "BCS Examination", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n\nThe '''Bangladesh Civil Service''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09bf\u09b8\u09bf\u098f\u09b8 \u09aa\u09b0\u09c0\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09be|\u09ac\u09bf\u09b8\u09bf\u098f\u09b8 \u09aa\u09b0\u09c0\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09be}}; BCS) is a nationwide competitive examination in Bangladesh conducted by the Bangladesh Public Service Commission (BPSC) for recruitment to the various [[Bangladesh Civil Service]] cadres, including BCS (Admin), BCS (Taxation), BCS (Foreign Affairs), and BCS (Police) among others.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The examination is conducted in three phases - the preliminary examination, the written examination and the viva voce (interview). The entire process from the notification of the preliminary examination to declaration of the final results takes 1.5 to 2 years.\n\n==Process==\nBangladesh Civil Service Examination is based on the [[British Raj]] - era [[Imperial Civil Service]]. The Civil Services Examination of Bangladesh is considered as the top most competitive job examination in Bangladesh. On an average, 150,000 to 225,000 candidates apply every year and the percentage of candidates appearing is roughly 90%. Aspirants must complete a three-stage process, with a final success rate of about 0.02% for all cadres and 0.005% for general cadres, although it varies from years to years exam.\n\n*'''Phase I''': Preliminary examination - This is qualifying test usually held in May/June every year. Notification for this is published about one month before the exam. Results are published about one month after the exam.\n*'''Phase II''': Written examination - This is the main test, usually held in October/November/December every year. Notification for this is published about one month before the exam. Results are usually published 6 to 10 months after the exam.\n*'''Phase III''': Viva Voce (Interview) - It is the oral test and is held after the publication of written result.\nFinal result is published about 1.5 to 2 months after finishing the viva voce.\n\n==Eligibility==\nThe eligibility norms for the examination are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Nationality===\nAll candidates must be Bangladeshi citizens. Candidates who are committed to marry or thereby engaged to foreign nationals should apply for a Permit/NOC to the Government of People's Republic of Bangladesh; applications can not be made without a Permit/NOC.\n\n===Age===\n*21 to 30 years (for General candidates)\n\n*The maximum age limit of freedom fighters and their sons daughters, disable candidate and BCS (Health) cadre candidates is 32(Thirty two)\n\n[http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/site/page/4bc95017-18d6-412b-8c4f-76d3e1599d8e/%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%8F%E0%A6%B8-%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7%E0%A6%BE '''details''']\n\n===Academic===\nMaster's degree or 4-year bachelor's degree after Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC) Exam. More than one-third class in any academic phase is considered as disqualification of a candidate.\n\n===Criticism of the quota system===\nCurrent policy of the quota system is highly criticized by the civil society members and intellectuals. Further continuation of freedom fighter quota among their children and grandchildren is highly controversial and, to some extent, a violation of Article 19 and 29 of the [[Constitution of Bangladesh]]. The students demonstrated a mass protest against this quota system in 2013.\nOn April 8, 2018, students of Dhaka University began a protest to reform the Quota, however police force shot rubber bullets and teargas shells at the protestors. Two students lost their eyes and many other were admitted to DMCH due to their injuries.<ref>http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=177669:protesters-to-siege-varsities-tomorrow-demanding-cancellation-of-bcs-quota-system&catid=187:online-edition&Itemid=223</ref><ref>http://www.bdchronicle.com/detail/news/31/810</ref>\n[[Bangladesh Anti Quota Protests 2013|Anti Quota Protests]] were spread to other parts of the country which made this protest a vital political issue. The Prime minister of Bangladesh committed to remove this quota system as soon as possible.\n\n==Preliminary examination==\nThis examination is a screening test conducted on the following pattern:\nSubject : [[Bengali language|Bengali]] - 35 Questions, English - 35 Questions, General Knowledge on Bangladesh & International Affairs - 50 Questions, General Science and computer - 30 Questions, Mathematical Reasoning and Mental Ability - 30 Questions, ethics and good governance -10, geography-10. The authority has published BCS Syllabus. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://teletalkbd.com/bcs-syllabus|title=BCS syllabus|work=teletalkbd.com|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n*Duration: 2 hours\n*Marks: 200\n*Question type: Objective<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Main exams==\n\n===Written examination===\n\n====General cadre====\nNine Compulsory subjects<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*General Bengali (Part I & II) = 200 Marks\n*General English (Part I & II)  = 200 Marks\n*Bangladesh Affairs (Part I & II)  = 200 Marks\n*International Affairs = 100 Marks\n*Mathematical Reasoning and Mental Ability = 100 Marks \n*General Science and Technology  = 100 Marks\n\n====Technical cadre====\nSeven compulsory subjects and two post related subjects.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*General Bengali = 100 Marks\n*General English (Part I & II) = 200 Marks\n*Bangladesh Affairs (Part I & II) = 200 Marks\n*International Affairs = 100 Marks\n*Mathematical Reasoning and Mental Ability = 100 Marks\n*Two Papers for post Related subject = 200 Marks\n\n====Both cadre====\nOne applying for both cadres: Nine compulsory subjects and two post related subjects\n\n===Viva voce (interview)===\nCandidates who pass the written phase successfully are qualified for the interview commonly known as viva voce. Success rate in this rigorous phase is quite lower than other phases. Current marks allocation for viva voce is 200.\n\n==Final selection==\nBPSC selects the candidates on the basis of the aggregated marks of written (obtained marks out of 900) and viva voce (obtained marks out of 200). 45% of the selection was made on the basis of merit and rest 55% according to several quotas. But now that the quota system has been cancelled, 100% of the selection will be held based on merit.\nBPSC recommends the selected qualified candidates to the Ministry of Public Administration.<ref>http://mopa.gov.bd/</ref> The ministry publishes the gazette of the selected candidates after a rigorous inspection of medical test by DGHS,<ref>http://www.dghs.gov.bd/index.php/en/</ref> [[Bangladesh Police|Police]] verification and [[National Security Intelligence|NSI]] verification.\nGenerally, the entire process from the advertisement to the final date of joining takes 1 year.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bangladesh Civil Service]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/ Bangladesh Public Service Commission official website]\n* [http://mopa.gov.bd/index.php Ministry of Public Administration official website]\n\n[[Category:Civil service in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Government recruitment]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n\nThe '''Bangladesh Civil Service''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09bf\u09b8\u09bf\u098f\u09b8 \u09aa\u09b0\u09c0\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09be|\u09ac\u09bf\u09b8\u09bf\u098f\u09b8 \u09aa\u09b0\u09c0\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09be}}; BCS) is a nationwide competitive examination in Bangladesh conducted by the Bangladesh Public Service Commission (BPSC) for recruitment to the various [[Bangladesh Civil Service]] cadres, including BCS (Admin), BCS (Taxation), BCS (Foreign Affairs), and BCS (Police) among others.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The examination is conducted in three phases - the preliminary examination, the written examination and the viva voce (interview). The entire process from the notification of the preliminary examination to declaration of the final results takes 1.5 to 2 years.\n\n==Process==\nBangladesh Civil Service Examination is based on the [[British Raj]] - era [[Imperial Civil Service]]. The Civil Services Examination of Bangladesh is considered as the top most competitive job examination in Bangladesh. On an average, 150,000 to 225,000 candidates apply every year and the percentage of candidates appearing is roughly 90%. Aspirants must complete a three-stage process, with a final success rate of about 0.02% for all cadres and 0.005% for general cadres, although it varies from years to years exam.\n\n*'''Phase I''': Preliminary examination - This is qualifying test usually held in May/June every year. Notification for this is published about one month before the exam. Results are published about one month after the exam.\n*'''Phase II''': Written examination - This is the main test, usually held in October/November/December every year. Notification for this is published about one month before the exam. Results are usually published 6 to 10 months after the exam.\n*'''Phase III''': Viva Voce (Interview) - It is the oral test and is held after the publication of written result.\nFinal result is published about 1.5 to 2 months after finishing the viva voce.\n\n==Eligibility==\nThe eligibility norms for the examination are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Nationality===\nAll candidates must be Bangladeshi citizens. Candidates who are committed to marry or thereby engaged to foreign nationals should apply for a Permit/NOC to the Government of People's Republic of Bangladesh; applications can not be made without a Permit/NOC.\n\n===Age===\n*21 to 30 years (for General candidates)\n\n*The maximum age limit of freedom fighters and their sons daughters, disable candidate and BCS (Health) cadre candidates is 32(Thirty two)\n\n[http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/site/page/4bc95017-18d6-412b-8c4f-76d3e1599d8e/%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%8F%E0%A6%B8-%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7%E0%A6%BE '''details''']\n\n===Academic===\nMaster's degree or 4-year bachelor's degree after Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC) Exam. More than one-third class in any academic phase is considered as disqualification of a candidate.\n\n===Criticism of the quota system===\nCurrent policy of the quota system is highly criticized by the civil society members and intellectuals. Further continuation of freedom fighter quota among their children and grandchildren is highly controversial and, to some extent, a violation of Article 19 and 29 of the [[Constitution of Bangladesh]]. The students demonstrated a mass protest against this quota system in 2013.\nOn April 8, 2018, students of Dhaka University began a protest to reform the Quota, however police force shot rubber bullets and teargas shells at the protestors. Two students lost their eyes and many other were admitted to DMCH due to their injuries.<ref>http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=177669:protesters-to-siege-varsities-tomorrow-demanding-cancellation-of-bcs-quota-system&catid=187:online-edition&Itemid=223</ref><ref>http://www.bdchronicle.com/detail/news/31/810</ref>\n[[Bangladesh Anti Quota Protests 2013|Anti Quota Protests]] were spread to other parts of the country which made this protest a vital political issue. The Prime minister of Bangladesh committed to remove this quota system as soon as possible.\n\n==Preliminary examination==\nThis examination is a screening test conducted on the following pattern:\nSubject : [[Bengali language|Bengali]] - 35 Questions, English - 35 Questions, General Knowledge on Bangladesh & International Affairs - 50 Questions, General Science and computer - 30 Questions, Mathematical Reasoning and Mental Ability - 30 Questions, ethics and good governance -10, geography-10. The authority has published BCS Syllabus. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://teletalkbd.com/bcs-syllabus|title=BCS Syllabuss|work=teletalkbd.com|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n*Duration: 2 hours\n*Marks: 200\n*Question type: Objective<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Main exams==\n\n===Written examination===\n\n====General cadre====\nNine Compulsory subjects<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*General Bengali (Part I & II) = 200 Marks\n*General English (Part I & II)  = 200 Marks\n*Bangladesh Affairs (Part I & II)  = 200 Marks\n*International Affairs = 100 Marks\n*Mathematical Reasoning and Mental Ability = 100 Marks \n*General Science and Technology  = 100 Marks\n\n====Technical cadre====\nSeven compulsory subjects and two post related subjects.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029224540/http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/platform/node/61.bpsc2012.pml |archive-date=29 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*General Bengali = 100 Marks\n*General English (Part I & II) = 200 Marks\n*Bangladesh Affairs (Part I & II) = 200 Marks\n*International Affairs = 100 Marks\n*Mathematical Reasoning and Mental Ability = 100 Marks\n*Two Papers for post Related subject = 200 Marks\n\n====Both cadre====\nOne applying for both cadres: Nine compulsory subjects and two post related subjects\n\n===Viva voce (interview)===\nCandidates who pass the written phase successfully are qualified for the interview commonly known as viva voce. Success rate in this rigorous phase is quite lower than other phases. Current marks allocation for viva voce is 200.\n\n==Final selection==\nBPSC selects the candidates on the basis of the aggregated marks of written (obtained marks out of 900) and viva voce (obtained marks out of 200). 45% of the selection was made on the basis of merit and rest 55% according to several quotas. But now that the quota system has been cancelled, 100% of the selection will be held based on merit.\nBPSC recommends the selected qualified candidates to the Ministry of Public Administration.<ref>http://mopa.gov.bd/</ref> The ministry publishes the gazette of the selected candidates after a rigorous inspection of medical test by DGHS,<ref>http://www.dghs.gov.bd/index.php/en/</ref> [[Bangladesh Police|Police]] verification and [[National Security Intelligence|NSI]] verification.\nGenerally, the entire process from the advertisement to the final date of joining takes 1 year.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bangladesh Civil Service]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bpsc.gov.bd/ Bangladesh Public Service Commission official website]\n* [http://mopa.gov.bd/index.php Ministry of Public Administration official website]\n\n[[Category:Civil service in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Government recruitment]]\n", "name_user": "Hafsa4g", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePreliminary examination", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BCS_Examination"}
{"title_page": "Trick of the Eye", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Trick of the Eye\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{hlist|Mystery|Thriller}}\n| based_on             = ''Trick of the Eye'' (novel) by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]\n| writer               = [[John Gay (screenwriter)|John Gay]]<br>[[Ken and Jim Wheat]]\n| director             = Ed Kaplan\n| starring             = [[Ellen Burstyn]]<br>[[Meg Tilly]]<br>[[Barnard Hughes]]<br>[[Paxton Whitehead]]<br>[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]]\n| music                = [[Allyn Ferguson]] \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = [[David A. Rosemont]]<br>[[Brent Shields]]\n| executive_producer   = Richard Welsh\n| location             = [[Pasadena, California]]\n| editor               = Sabrina Plisco-Morris\n| cinematography       = [[Shelly Johnson (cinematographer)|Shelly Johnson]]\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| company              = Signboard Hill Productions<br>[[Sonar Entertainment|Hallmark Entertainment]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1994|10|23}}\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Trick of the Eye''''' (also known as '''''Primal Secrets''''') is a 1994 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[psychological thriller|psychological thriller film]] starring [[Ellen Burstyn]] and [[Meg Tilly]]. Directed by Ed Kaplan, it is based on the 1992 novel of the same name by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]. The film originally premiered on [[CBS]] as a presentation of ''CBS Sunday Afternoon Showcase'' on October 23, 1994.\n\n==Plot==\nFaith Crowell (Meg Tilly) is a struggling bohemian artist who is commissioned to paint a mural for wealthy, reclusive socialite widow Frances Griffin (Ellen Burstyn). Frances wants Faith to paint murals all over the ornate walls of the abandoned ballroom of her ostentatious 211-acre estate. The theme of the mural is to be the grand entrance of Frances' daughter Cassandra at her debutante ball, which also happens to be the night Cassandra mysteriously died.\n\nFaith soon begins receiving expensive gifts from Frances, which she enjoys but doesn't understand why. Before long, Faith starts picking up on several uncanny resemblances between herself and the dead Cassandra. Eventually, she is invited to live in Frances' mansion until the mural is complete, and she discovers a painting of Cassandra and sees the haunting resemblance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ellen Burstyn]] as Frances Griffin\n*[[Meg Tilly]] as Faith Crowell\n*[[Barnard Hughes]] as Harry Pitt\n*[[Paxton Whitehead]] as Deane\n*[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]] as Simon\n*[[Romy Rosemont]] as Cathy Newman\n\n==Production==\n''Trick of the Eye'' was shot from August 8 to August 31, 1994 at [[Huntington Library]] in [[Pasadena, California]]\n\n==Home video releases==\nIn July 1995, the film was released under the alternative title ''Primal Secrets'' on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] by [[Crown Media Holdings|Hallmark Home Entertainment]] and [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].\n\nOn January 25, 2010, it was released as ''Primal Secrets'' on [[DVD]] by [[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]].\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/475633/Trick-of-the-Eye/misc-notes.html ''Trick of the Eye'': Miscellaneous Notes] at [[Turner Classic Movies|TCM]] (1994).\n#[https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-trick-of-the-eye-vol-42-no-17/ Picks and Pans Review: Trick of the Eye] by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine (October 24, 1994).\n#[https://www.lddb.com/laserdisc/06525/ID3185HL/Primal-Secrets-(Trick-of-the-Eye) ''Trick of the Eye/Primal Secrets''] at LaserDisc Database (1995)\n#[https://www.amazon.com/Primal-Secrets-Ellen-Burstyn/dp/B0009ETCYC/ref=sr_1_9?dchild=1&keywords=primal+secrets&qid=1587029441&s=movies-tv&sr=1-9 ''Trick of the Eye/Primal Secrets''] at [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0111490|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{tcmdb title|475633|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{Amg movie|178294|Trick of the Eye}}\n\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1994 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s mystery films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Long Island]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n\n{{US-tv-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Trick of the Eye\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{hlist|Mystery|Thriller}}\n| based_on             = ''Trick of the Eye'' (novel) by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]\n| writer               = [[John Gay (screenwriter)|John Gay]]<br>[[Ken and Jim Wheat]]\n| director             = Ed Kaplan\n| starring             = [[Ellen Burstyn]]<br>[[Meg Tilly]]<br>[[Barnard Hughes]]<br>[[Paxton Whitehead]]<br>[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]]\n| music                = [[Allyn Ferguson]] \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = [[David A. Rosemont]]<br>[[Brent Shields]]\n| executive_producer   = Richard Welsh\n| location             = [[Pasadena, California]]\n| editor               = Sabrina Plisco-Morris\n| cinematography       = [[Shelly Johnson (cinematographer)|Shelly Johnson]]\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| company              = Signboard Hill Productions<br>[[Sonar Entertainment|Hallmark Entertainment]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1994|10|23}}\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Trick of the Eye''''' (also known as '''''Primal Secrets''''') is a 1994 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[psychological thriller|psychological thriller film]] starring [[Ellen Burstyn]] and [[Meg Tilly]]. Directed by Ed Kaplan, it is based on the 1992 novel of the same name by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]. The film originally premiered on [[CBS]] as a presentation of ''CBS Sunday Afternoon Showcase'' on October 23, 1994.\n\n==Plot==\nFaith Crowell (Meg Tilly) is a struggling bohemian artist who is commissioned to paint a mural for wealthy, reclusive socialite widow Frances Griffin (Ellen Burstyn). Frances wants Faith to paint murals all over the ornate walls of the abandoned ballroom of her ostentatious 211-acre estate. The theme of the mural is to be the grand entrance of Frances' daughter Cassandra at her debutante ball, which also happens to be the night Cassandra mysteriously died.\n\nFaith soon begins receiving expensive gifts from Frances, which she enjoys but doesn't understand why. Before long, Faith starts picking up on several uncanny resemblances between herself and the dead Cassandra. Eventually, she is invited to live in Frances' mansion until the mural is complete, and she discovers a painting of Cassandra and sees the haunting resemblance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ellen Burstyn]] as Frances Griffin\n*[[Meg Tilly]] as Faith Crowell\n*[[Barnard Hughes]] as Harry Pitt\n*[[Paxton Whitehead]] as Deane\n*[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]] as Simon\n*[[Romy Rosemont]] as Cathy Newman\n\n==Production==\n''Trick of the Eye'' was shot from August 8 to August 31, 1994 at [[Huntington Library]] in [[Pasadena, California]]\n\n==Home video releases==\nIn July 1995, the film was released under the alternative title ''Primal Secrets'' on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] by [[Crown Media Holdings|Hallmark Home Entertainment]] and [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].\n\nOn January 25, 2010, it was released as ''Primal Secrets'' on [[DVD]] by [[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]].\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/475633/Trick-of-the-Eye/misc-notes.html ''Trick of the Eye'': Miscellaneous Notes] at [[Turner Classic Movies|TCM]] (1994).\n#[https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-trick-of-the-eye-vol-42-no-17/ Picks and Pans Review: Trick of the Eye] by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine (October 24, 1994).\n#[https://www.lddb.com/laserdisc/06525/ID3185HL/Primal-Secrets-(Trick-of-the-Eye) ''Trick of the Eye/Primal Secrets''] at LaserDisc Database (1995)\n#[https://www.amazon.com/Primal-Secrets-Ellen-Burstyn/dp/B0009ETCYC/ref=sr_1_9?dchild=1&keywords=primal+secrets&qid=1587029441&s=movies-tv&sr=1-9 ''Trick of the Eye/Primal Secrets''] at [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0111490|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{tcmdb title|475633|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{Amg movie|178294|Trick of the Eye}}\n\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1994 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s mystery films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n\n{{US-tv-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trick_of_the_Eye"}
